# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: seven-network
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:seven-network/10-comedy] The channel focuses primarily on programming targeting a young adult audience and was the home of *Neighbours*—the longest-running drama series on Australian television.
[src:seven-network/10-comedy] Prior to the launch of Nickelodeon, the channel also aired children's programming.
[src:seven-network/10-comedy] Prior to the launch of the channel, Ten Network Holdings, at the time an independent company, established a joint venture company named ElevenCo with international distributor CBS Studios International.
[src:seven-network/10-comedy] 10 held a two-thirds equity stake in the venture, with CBS holding the remaining share.
[src:seven-network/10-comedy] Under the arrangement, Eleven gained access to programming from CBS's back catalogue.
[src:seven-network/10-comedy] Ten Network Holdings entered administration in 2017 and was subsequently acquired by CBS Corporation, ultimately giving CBS full ownership of Eleven.
[src:seven-network/10-comedy] CBS ultimately merged with Viacom, making 10 Comedy a sister network to MTV and Nickelodeon.
[src:seven-network/10-comedy] On 31 October 2018, the channel rebranded as **10 Peach**, as part of a larger rebranding of Network Ten.
[src:seven-network/10-comedy] On 5 June 2024, it was announced that 10 Peach would rebrand to 10 Peach Comedy on 12 June 2024, as part of a rebranding of Bold and Peach to reflect their genre positionings.
[src:seven-network/10-comedy] On 30 June 2025, the channel shortened its name to 10 Comedy as part of a rebranding of Network 10.
[src:seven-network/10-comedy] 10 Comedy offers catch-up and encore presentations from Channel 10.
[src:seven-network/10-comedy] It features a mix of repeated classic programs, new shows to Australian television, and shows that would make their debut on Australian free-to-air television.
[src:seven-network/10-comedy] Most of the classic programming on 10 Comedy comprises 80's, 90's and 2000's comedies and dramas sourced from Paramount Television, CBS Studios and CBS Studios International (via parent company Paramount Global).
[src:seven-network/10-comedy] Some of Ten's shows aimed at a younger demographic, most notably *Neighbours*, were moved to Eleven for the launch of the new channel.
[src:seven-network/10-comedy] This was part of Ten's re-branding to target the older demographic.
[src:seven-network/10-comedy] The decision to move *Neighbours* and other shows was to also make way for a new current affairs show in Ten's 6:00–7:00pm timeslot.
[src:seven-network/10-comedy] In 2015 *Neighbours* was Eleven's highest-rating program and the number-one regular Australian program on the digital multichannels, averaging 278,000 viewers.
[src:seven-network/10-comedy] On 27 February 2012, *Toasted TV* was moved from Ten to Eleven due to a number of changes to their morning line-up, which included the launch of *Breakfast*.
[src:seven-network/10-comedy] On 4 November 2013, more of Ten's shows including *Totally Wild*, *Scope*, *Wurrawhy* and *Mako: Island of Secrets* moved due to the launch of *Wake Up* and *Studio 10*.
[src:seven-network/10-comedy] Other first-run Australian content on 10 Comedy includes *Couch Time*, *The Loop* and *Bondi Ink Tattoo*.
[src:seven-network/10-comedy] On 6 April 2020, a six-hour programming block of Nickelodeon children's content was added to the network, which aired under the *Toasted TV* branding.
[src:seven-network/10-comedy] This ran until 27 September, when children's programming was entirely moved to 10 Shake.
[src:seven-network/10-comedy] The network also has ongoing content new and classic film and television brands from Paramount Pictures, DreamWorks Pictures, MTV Entertainment Studios, Miramax and Paramount Players.
[src:seven-network/10-comedy] The channel is also available to regional Australia viewers through Seven West Media's owned-and-operated stations SGS/SCN in Spencer Gulf and Broken Hill, MGS/LRS in eastern South Australia, WIN Television owned and operated stations MDN in Griffith and the MIA.
[src:seven-network/10-comedy] Digital joint venture stations WDT in regional Western Australia, TDT in Tasmania, DTD in Darwin, and CDT in Remote Central & Eastern Australia also carry 10 Comedy.
[src:seven-network/10-drama] The channel commenced broadcasting as **One HD** on 26 March 2009 at 7.00pm in Melbourne (due to live coverage of the Australian Football League) and at 7.30pm in Sydney, Brisbane, Adelaide and Perth.
[src:seven-network/10-drama] The channel, owned by Network 10, featured nonstop sport content including live sport, sports documentaries and sports-themed movies.
[src:seven-network/10-drama] One initially broadcast in high definition on digital channels 1 and 11 with a standard-definition simulcast on digital channel 12 known as **One SD** or **One Digital**.
[src:seven-network/10-drama] At launch, One replaced the previous Ten HD service and a standard-definition simulcast of Ten HD called TenSD2.
[src:seven-network/10-drama] One HD began broadcasting on Macquarie Media Group's owned and operated Southern Cross Ten regional television stations on digital channel 50 at 7.00pm on 2 July 2009.
[src:seven-network/10-drama] Tasmania did not broadcast it until 30 July 2009, and Mildura did not broadcast it until 1 December 2009.
[src:seven-network/10-drama] The simulcast on digital channel 11 was later reallocated for Ten's standard-definition digital multichannel Eleven (now 10 Comedy) on 15 December 2010 in preparation for its launch on 11 January 2011.
[src:seven-network/10-drama] As a result, the channel's high definition simulcast was moved to channel 12, replacing the standard-definition simulcast.
[src:seven-network/10-drama] In 2011, the channel began to dilute its all-sport format to include adventure-themed reality programming such as *Ice Road Truckers* and *Black Gold*, and a weekly feature-length movie or documentary, usually, but not limited to, a sporting theme.
[src:seven-network/10-drama] In April 2011, it was revealed that the channel would shift to a more broad general entertainment channel aimed towards a younger male demographic, whilst still featuring sports programming.
[src:seven-network/10-drama] The changes were intended to make the channel a greater competitor against 7mate, which has a similar scope, and took place on 8 May 2011.
[src:seven-network/10-drama] As a result of the revival of 10 HD on 2 March 2016, the channel was reduced to standard definition.
[src:seven-network/10-drama] On 31 October 2018, One relaunched as 10 Boss, as part of a larger rebranding of Network Ten.
[src:seven-network/10-drama] Chief content officer Beverley McGarvey described "Boss" as reflecting an overall "attitude" in its programming, exemplified by a focus on characters with "bold" personalities or could be reasonably described as being a "boss" (such as *Judge Judy*).
[src:seven-network/10-drama] 10 Boss primarily targets viewers over the age of 40, and focuses primarily on dramas (such as *Madam Secretary* and *NCIS*).
[src:seven-network/10-drama] On 10 December 2018, the channel was renamed 10 Bold, due to trademark conflicts with Fairfax Media (which had completed its merger with Nine Entertainment Co.) and the *Australian Financial Review* publication *Boss*.
[src:seven-network/10-drama] A press release promoting the rebranding acknowledged the conflict, describing the change as being an "early Christmas present to Nine", and quipping that "it's better to be bold than bossy".
[src:seven-network/10-drama] On 5 June 2024, it was announced that the channel would rebrand as 10 Bold Drama on 12 June 2024, as part of a rebranding of Bold and Peach to include their main genres in their names.
[src:seven-network/10-drama] On 30 June 2025, the channel shortened its name to 10 Drama as part of a rebranding of Network 10.
[src:seven-network/10-drama] The channel targets a broad range of viewers, broadcasting programs from Australia, New Zealand, the United Kingdom, Canada, and the United States, and complementing existing programming on Network 10.
[src:seven-network/10-drama] Programs aired on the channel are scripted and adventure-based programming aimed at males between the ages of 25 and 54, mix of genres, including reality, lifestyle, drama, classic sitcoms from the 60s, 70s and 80s, comedies, live sport and action films.
[src:seven-network/10-drama] In 2008, prior to the channel launching, Ten secured the rights for both the 2010 & 2014 editions of the Commonwealth Games, simulcasting on the channel.
[src:seven-network/10-drama] For the 2010 games in Delhi, it was also shared with Foxtel.
[src:seven-network/10-drama] On 17 March 2009, the Australian Swimming Championships was broadcast on Ten HD before the launch of the channel on 26 March 2009 showing Live in 2009 until 2015, when the Seven Network secured a nine-year deal with Swimming Australia.
[src:seven-network/10-drama] The channel had previously showed NASCAR, between 2010 and 2014 airing both Sprint Cup and Nationwide Series highlights.
[src:seven-network/10-drama] Every NASCAR Sprint Cup race was shown live between 2011 and 2014.
[src:seven-network/10-drama] In October 2011, it was confirmed that the National Basketball League games would be delayed.
[src:seven-network/10-drama] During the 2012–13 season, some Friday night games were shown live on the channel at 9.30pm.
[src:seven-network/10-drama] Live Sunday games returned to 10 at 2pm.
[src:seven-network/10-drama] By March 2012, sport was very much a secondary focus of 10 Bold.
[src:seven-network/10-drama] Sport is only shown when it clashes with 10's regular programming or as HD simulcast when it airs on 10.
[src:seven-network/10-drama] Moto GP races airs only on 10 Bold except for the Australian GP round which airs on 10 as well as 10 Drama as HD simulcast.
[src:seven-network/10-drama] F1 qualifying is shown on 10 Bold live while 10 replays later on.
[src:seven-network/10-drama] 10 Drama broadcast Moto GP every race live (qualifying in highlights only from 2014 onwards) from 2010 till 2014, then from 2015 to 2016.
[src:seven-network/10-drama] Moto2 and Moto3 and MotoGP will be shown on the Australian Motorcycle Grand Prix round only on Ten.
[src:seven-network/10-drama] In 2016, the channel showed highlights for every round of Super Rugby every Sunday morning and replays of every Wallabies Test at around midday, that was previously shown on TEN from The Rugby Championship and Spring Tour.
[src:seven-network/10-drama] In May 2021, it was announced that Network 10 would have rights to the A-Leagues men's and women's competition, with all games being streamed on 10's paid streaming service Paramount+ and women's games to be shown for free on 10play.
[src:seven-network/10-drama] The current 2024–25 season, two A-League men games will be shown on 10 Drama every Saturday week.
[src:seven-network/10-drama] It is also available in regional Australia in 576i standard definition from Seven West Media's owned-and-operated stations, SGS/SCN in Spencer Gulf and Broken Hill.
[src:seven-network/10-drama] WIN Television through its owned-and-operated stations, MGS/LRS in eastern South Australia, and MDN in Griffith and the MIA.
[src:seven-network/10-drama] Digital joint-venture stations, TDT in Tasmania, WDT in regional Western Australia, DTD in Darwin, and CDT in Central Australia (including remote NT, QLD, NSW and SA) also broadcast 10 Drama but in 1080i high definition just like 10 Drama in 10's O&O stations.
[src:seven-network/10-drama] Due to the relaunch of 10 HD on 2 March 2016, the channel was reduced to a standard-definition television channel in metropolitan areas for 5 years until 23 September 2021 at 6am when it switched back to a high-definition channel.
[src:seven-network/10-drama] One was available to Foxtel cable subscribers via its HD+ package, and One SD was available on its basic cable service when it was broadcast.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] As of 2025, Network 10 is the fourth-rated television network and primary channel in Australia, behind the Seven Network, Nine Network and ABC TV and ahead of SBS.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] From the introduction of TV in 1956 until 1965, there were three television networks in Australia, the National Television Network (now the Nine Network), the Australian Television Network (now the Seven Network), and the public ABC National Television Service (now ABC TV).
[src:seven-network/10-hd] In the early 1960s, the Australian Government began canvassing the idea of licensing a third commercial television station in each capital city.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] This decision was seen by some as a way for the government to defuse growing public dissatisfaction with the dominance of imported overseas programming and the paucity of local content.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] The first of these third licences was granted to United Telecasters (a consortium of Amalgamated Wireless, Colonial Sugar Refining Company, Email, Bank of New South Wales and the NRMA) on 4 April 1963.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] Structurally, the Australian television industry was closely modelled on the two-tiered system that had been in place in Australian radio since the late 1930s.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] One tier consisted of a network of publicly funded television stations run by the ABC, which was funded by government budget allocation and (until 1972) by fees from television viewer licences.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] The second tier consisted of the commercial networks and independent stations owned by private operators, whose income came from selling advertising time.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] The network was launched as ATV-0 in Melbourne opened on 1 August 1964 and was owned by the Ansett Transport Industries, which at the time owned one of Australia's two domestic airlines.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] TEN-10 in Sydney, which opened on 5 April 1965, was originally owned by United Telecasters, which also in July that year opened TVQ-0 in Brisbane.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] Also opened later that month was SAS-10, serving the city of Adelaide.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] The new television network was initially dubbed the **Independent Television System** or ITS, but in 1970 adopted the title **The 0-10 Network**, which reflected the channels used by the first two stations launched in the group, ATV and TEN.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] Melbourne's ATV was the first station of the network to stage colour broadcasts in 1967; the broadcast was of the horse races in Pakenham, Victoria, and was seen by network and RCA executives and invited members of the media and press.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] This would be the first of many test colour telecasts for the station, and in 1974, in tribute to the event, the 0-10 Network adopted the *First in Colour* slogan, months before the 1 March 1975 transition to colour broadcasting.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] For its first five years, the 0-10 Network led a hand-to-mouth existence.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] By the beginning of the 1970s the network was in a precarious financial position and there were predictions that it would fail.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] In 1971, the 0-10 Network first aired *Young Talent Time*, which was a huge rating success, and ran for 17 years.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] However, the network's true financial reprise came about due to the fact that the controversial adult soap opera serial *Number 96* premiered in March 1972 on the night that "Australian TV lost its virginity".
[src:seven-network/10-hd] The series broke new ground for Australian television and captured the imagination of viewers like few programs before or since.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] For the next three years it was consistently Australia's top-rating television program and, not surprisingly, its huge popularity attracted advertisers to Ten *en masse*, with the result that its revenue increased significantly from $1 million in 1971 to more than $10 million in 1972.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] However, the pattern of rating dominance was already set, and for most of the next five decades from the mid-1960s, there was little deviation from the prevalent rankings, with the Nine Network typically in the first place, the Seven Network second, 0-10 third and ABC TV fourth.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] The gradual evolution of Network Ten into its current form has its origins in the ongoing attempts by media mogul Rupert Murdoch to acquire a prized commercial television licence in Australia's largest capital city market, Sydney.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] This began when Murdoch's News Limited purchased the Wollongong station WIN-4 in the early 1960s, around the same time he bought Festival Records.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] In 1977, frustrated by regulatory blocks that prevented him from expanding into the Sydney market, Murdoch sold WIN and purchased a 46% share in Ten Sydney.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] In 1979, Murdoch made an unsuccessful takeover bid for the Melbourne-based The Herald and Weekly Times media group, which originally owned HSV-7.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] Although the bid failed, he gained a 50% stake in Ansett, which thus gave him control of channel 0 in Melbourne.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] In 1979, 0-10 first aired the soap opera *Prisoner*, which was a huge rating success.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] On 20 January 1980, the 0-10 Network became known as **Network Ten** to reflect ATV moving from channel 0 to channel 10 – although the Brisbane station continued to broadcast as TVQ-0 until 10 September 1988 when the station changed to TVQ-10.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] In 1987 Adelaide's Network Ten affiliate (SAS-10) and Seven Network affiliate (ADS-7) successfully negotiated to exchange affiliation rights and channel frequencies due to ownership problems.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] On 27 December 1987, the exchange came into effect and ADS-7, owned by the same owners as the main Network Ten stations, became ADS-10 with SAS-10 converting to SAS-7, operated by TVW-7 in Perth.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] However, Westfield was badly hit by the stock market crash of 1987, and in 1989 sold Network Ten to a consortium led by Charles Curran and former television journalist Steve Cosser.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] The network became fully national in 1988 with the launch of NEW-10 in Perth after the introduction of satellite facilities made it economical for the network to broadcast to Western Australia.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] Northern Star officially took hold of TVQ-10 later in the year because of swapping frequencies with neighbouring DDQ-0 in Toowoomba and rebranded CTC Canberra under the network banner in time for aggregation.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] In 1989, Ten's ratings were in decline, so on 23 July 1989, recently recruited network boss Bob Shanks relaunched the network, re-branding it as **10 TV Australia**, and introducing several new programs, including four new prime time game shows.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] However, by the end of 1989, the ratings failed to improve and most of the new programs were cancelled, except for its *Eyewitness News* bulletins, *Neighbours* and *E Street* (debuting in late 1988).
[src:seven-network/10-hd] Meanwhile, Northern Star Holdings were having financial and regulatory problems.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] The company was subject to an inquiry by the Australian Broadcasting Tribunal in relation to media ownership rules and had run into financial difficulties following the 1987 stock market crash two years earlier.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] On 1 September 1989, Northern Star Holdings announced a major restructuring to pay off debts and help restore profitability.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] The proposals included selling off the network's three smaller stations (ADS in Adelaide, NEW in Perth and CTC in Canberra) to Charles Curran's *Capital Television Group*.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] The sale was completed on 27 October 1989, effectively splitting Northern Star's Network Ten in half.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] In September 1990, Northern Star went into receivership and on 13 January 1991 at 8:30pm, the network was re-branded back to **Network Ten** with the first version of its famous *ten* watermark logo.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] The network was placed into liquidation by the New South Wales Rugby League in May 1991.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] In 1992, the network's flagship stations were sold to the Canadian-based Canwest media group, which held a controlling stake in the network until 2009.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] Also in 1992, the network commenced a strategy of targeting younger audiences.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] The Adelaide and Perth stations were re-acquired by the network in 1995.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] With the network having financially recovered, Ten Network Holdings floated on the Australian Stock Exchange in 1998.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] At this time, Ten had affiliate broadcasting agreements with Southern Cross Broadcasting in southern New South Wales, regional Victoria and Tasmania, and with Telecasters Australia in northern New South Wales and regional Queensland.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] In 2001, Ten opened the doors to the *Big Brother Australia* house and, with it, reality television.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] The opening night of *Big Brother* became the most-watched program of the night.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] *Big Brother* became synonymous with the network in the 2000s, with the series lasting 8 seasons.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] Even after iterations on rival networks, *Big Brother* is set to return to 10 in 2025.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] The trend was then followed by the launching of the Australian version of the reality singing competition format Idols called *Australian Idol* in 2003.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] *Australian Idol* was a hit for several years, lasting until 2009.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] In 2004, Network Ten enjoyed its best year since the 1970s, winning two rating weeks (out of 40) and finishing second nationally only behind the Nine Network and well ahead of the Seven Network.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] This was a departure from previous years; it has typically placed third behind Nine and Seven in most other rating years since 2000.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] In 2005, Canwest was in discussions with newspaper publisher John Fairfax Holdings about a possible sale of the network, after the federal government indicated it may consider relaxing Australia's media cross-ownership laws.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] Previously, newspaper owners could not own television stations in the same city.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] Fairfax owned the Seven Network until 1988 and had been looking for a way back into television for a long time.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] On 21 August 2005, the network celebrated its 40th birthday with a two-hour highlights package called *Ten: Seriously 40*, which was hosted by Bert Newton and Rove McManus.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] On 27 October 2005, Network Ten announced that its long-running morning talk-variety program *Good Morning Australia* would be cancelled at the end of the year after a fourteen-year run.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] This ended host Bert Newton's 14-year association with Network Ten; although he was offered ongoing employment with the network, he announced that he would be returning to the Nine Network.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] *9am with David & Kim* replaced GMA as Ten's national morning program from 2006 to 2009.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] From 2006 to 2008, Ten was the official broadcaster of Sydney New Year's Eve.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] The rights returned to the Nine Network from 2009.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] On 7 August 2007, Network Ten and Foxtel signed a new agreement allowing Ten's digital signal to be transmitted via Foxtel's cable and satellite services.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] Prior to this, Ten was only transmitted via cable on Foxtel in an analogue format and Austar in standard definition digital via Mystar.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] Similarly in October 2007, Network Ten and Optus announced that Ten's digital signal would be available on its cable network from 1 December 2007.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] On 16 December 2007, Ten HD was officially launched as a breakaway channel, becoming the first new commercial television channel in metropolitan areas of Australia since 1988.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] Ten HD ceased broadcasting on 25 March 2009 when it was replaced by what was a sports-only high-definition channel, One HD.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] On 24 September 2009, Canwest announced that it was selling its 50.1% stake in Ten Network Holdings for $680 million, to pay down its significant debt.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] In late 2009, Canwest filed for creditor bankruptcy protection, due to CA$4 billion mounting debt across radio, television broadcasting and publishing assets in several countries.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] On 20 October 2010, four years after he sold his shares in PBL Media to private equity firm CVC Asia Pacific, James Packer purchased 16 per cent of Ten.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] Network Ten launched a new digital channel, Eleven, on 11 January 2011.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] The channel is aimed at a "distinctly youthful" audience between the ages of 13 and 29.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] *Neighbours* and *The Simpsons* were high-profile programs migrating from Ten to the new channel.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] The channel was a joint venture with CBS Studios International, which owned a 33% stake.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] On 8 May 2011, Ten relaunched its sports-based channel One, with general entertainment programming aimed at males taking over the schedule.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] It is aimed at a similar audience to 7mate.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] In 2012, Ten unsuccessfully launched many new programs.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] This led to Ten's ratings dropping to fourth place behind ABC TV for over thirty straight nights.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] The poor performance resulted in Chief Programming Officer David Mott's resignation.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] In September 2012, Ten made a partnership with TVSN, which meant the TVSN channel became available on Ten's free-to-air multiplex to metropolitan viewers as a datacast service on LCN 14, on 24 September 2012.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] In late 2012, Ten reported a loss of $12.9m as it battled poor advertising markets and failed to hold larger audience numbers.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] They made positions at the station redundant and said that production may become centralised.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] Ten launched Spree TV, an Australian free-to-air datacasting television channel mainly carrying paid programming and home shopping, on 17 September 2013, on LCN 15, with Brand Developers.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] Analogue broadcasts ceased in the regions on 10 December 2013.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] On 1 August 2014, the network celebrated its 50th anniversary.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] A television special related to the anniversary called *50 Years Young* aired on 3 August 2014, after being rescheduled from 8 August by the network.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] On 15 June 2015, Foxtel (co-owned by News Corp) bought 15% shares in Ten Network Holdings, pending approval from the ACCC.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] Prior to the acquisition, Discovery backed out from a bidding partnership with Foxtel.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] In July 2015, Paul Anderson was announced as the new chief executive officer.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] A high-definition simulcast of 10 was revived on 2 March 2016.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] As a result, One, now known as 10 Bold, began broadcasting in standard definition only.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] On 29 April 2016, the Nine Network pulled its regional affiliation with WIN Television over a lawsuit involving its catch-up service 9Now, and announced a new affiliation agreement with Southern Cross Austereo, Ten's then-primary regional affiliate.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] WIN owner and Ten's largest shareholder Bruce Gordon positioned himself to increase his ownership stake in Ten, subject to changes to media ownership laws being passed.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] Following Ten Network Holdings reporting a $232 million half year loss, shareholders Lachlan Murdoch, Bruce Gordon and James Packer withdrew support for $250 million guaranteed loan that would help keep Ten out of receivership.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] This loan was intended to replace an existing guaranteed $200 million loan that was due to expire in December.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] On 13 June, Ten asked the Australian Securities Exchange that their stock be placed in a 48-hour trading halt while it assessed its options concerning receivership.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] It went into voluntary administration the following day.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] On 28 August 2017, Ten's administrators announced that the U.S. media company CBS Corporation (which had a 33% share in the multichannel Eleven and was Ten's largest creditor) had entered into a binding agreement to purchase the company for $123 million.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] CBS refinanced Ten's existing debt including guarantor fees to shareholders Packer, Murdoch and Gordon, and existing loans from the Commonwealth Bank.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] Shareholders in Ten Network Holdings lost their investment.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] Gordon and Murdoch had also placed their own joint bid for the company, which was not endorsed by the administrators.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] At a meeting held on 12 September, Ten's creditors overwhelmingly voted in support of CBS' bid, citing concerns over Murdoch's previous management of Ten and talk of mass job cuts in the news department under Murdoch/Gordon ownership.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] The CBS acquisition was completed on 16 November 2017, when the shares of Ten Network Holdings were transferred to CBS Network Ten BV, a company registered in the Netherlands.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] Following the CBS acquisition, the network became a division of CBS Studios International.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] Ten moved to commission more Australian content.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] The additional programs were financed by the savings from the dissolution of Ten's output agreement with 21st Century Fox.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] CBS also moved to re-establish an in-house advertising sales department for 2019, bringing to an end Ten's four-year period with the Foxtel-affiliated Multi Channel Network (MCN).
[src:seven-network/10-hd] One reason CBS acquired Ten was to assist the company to launch its CBS All Access streaming service in the Australian market.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] The service launched in December 2018 and was branded 10 All Access in the local market.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] On 31 October 2018, the network unveiled a new logo, replacing the "ten" wordmark used since 1991 with a stylised circle 10, and the network is now referred to in the text as **Network 10**.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] The new brand is used across all of Network 10's platforms and services, and was intended to reflect the broadcaster's positioning as an "adventurous alternative" with a "sense of fun".
[src:seven-network/10-hd] 10 also relaunched its multi channels Eleven and One as 10 Peach and 10 Boss, with Boss focusing on dramatic programming and targeting an older adult audience, and Peach continuing to be targeted towards young adults.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] 10 Boss was forced to change its name to 10 Bold on 10 December 2018 due to trademark conflicts with Fairfax Media.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] On 4 December 2019, CBS Corporation completed a re-merger with fellow media conglomerate Viacom as ViacomCBS; the two companies had previously separated in 2005.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] The following month, it was announced that the former Viacom channels in Australia would be brought under the Network 10 sales department, moving away from Foxtel Media (formerly MCN) in April.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] Network 10 also began to co-commission new programmes with Channel 5, including the drama miniseries *Lie With Me* and documentary series *The Royals Revealed*.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] On 13 July 2020, it was announced that Network 10 would launch a third digital channel, 10 Shake, on 27 September and on channel 13.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] On 16 September 2020, in 10's metropolitan areas, various Network 10 channels moved channel places due to the launch of Network 10's third digital channel *10 Shake*.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] The channels that moved places include TVSN, which moved to channel 16 from channel 14, 10 HD, which moved to channels 1 and 15 from channel 13 and Spree TV, which moved to channel 17 from channel 15.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] As a result, 10 Bold is now solely on channel 12.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] A placeholder for 10 Shake appeared on the same day.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] In March 2021, 10 announced that it would return to Southern Cross Austereo as its regional affiliate in most markets beginning on 1 July 2021, in a deal that will last at least two years.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] The agreement reversed 10's 2016 move to WIN, which had announced a long-term agreement to return to the Nine Network.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] In February 2022, Network 10 and Paramount+ announced that it had commissioned *NCIS: Sydney*, a spin-off of CBS's drama franchise *NCIS*.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] On 15 February 2022, it was announced that ViacomCBS would be rebranding as Paramount Global as part of a wide rebrand strategy.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] On 12 August 2022, Spree TV, the network's shopping channel, on channel 17, ceased to broadcast.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] It was replaced by Gecko, a similar shopping channel, on 18 September 2022.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] On 22 June 2023, it was announced that 10 Shake would rebrand as Nickelodeon on 1 August, featuring programmes under the Nick Jr., Nickelodeon, and Nick at Nite brands.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] The Foxtel pay television version of the channel subsequently closed down.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] On 5 June 2024, it was announced that 10 Peach and 10 Bold would be rebranded as 10 Peach Comedy and 10 Bold Drama on 12 June.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] On 17 December 2024, Southern Cross Austereo announced the sale of their regional television licenses in Regional QLD, Southern NSW/ACT and Regional Victoria to Network 10.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] As part of the sale, SCA will receive a share of profits from the stations for the first 5 years post-completion.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] On 13 February 2025, Network 10 announced they are also acquiring their affiliate in Northern NSW/Gold Coast from WIN Television, which was later completed on 1 May.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] Following the completion of both SCA and WIN acquisitions, Network 10 will directly own and operate the four main regional licenses across the eastern states of Australia, the second network after the Seven Network to do so.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] On 10 August 2026, Network 10 will launch 10+1, a free-to-air timeshift channel which broadcasts the main Channel 10 schedule with a one-hour delay.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] International Television Distribution, Sony Pictures Television and Transmission Films.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] When it was independent, 10 had a long-standing relationship with Paramount Global Content Distribution (then CBS Studios International) for the Australian TV rights to its content.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] On 27 October 2017, Network 10's studio output deal with 20th Century Fox was terminated due to the network's bankruptcy and the CBS acquisition of the network in the same year.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] Consequently, the network lost the TV rights to popular shows such as *The Simpsons*, *Modern Family*, *Fresh Off the Boat* and *Life in Pieces*, among others.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] Coincidentally, as of the acquisition of 21st Century Fox by Disney, a deal, with exceptions, was then picked up by Disney affiliate Seven Network.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] In 2018 however, 10 would create a newly acquired programming deal with Warner Bros. and Roadshow Entertainment, granting the network programming rights until 2025.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] Shared American programming which airs on 10 and Seven and its digital multi-channels are sourced from 10 and Seven's deals with Sony Pictures Television, CBS Studios and DreamWorks / DreamWorks Animation.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] Shared American programming which airs on 10 and Nine and its digital multi-channels are sourced from 10 and Nine's deals with Sony Pictures Television, CBS Studios, United International Pictures, DreamWorks / DreamWorks Animation and Warner Bros.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] Shared American programming that airs on 10 and ABC and its digital multi-channels are sourced from 10 and ABC's deals with Sony Pictures Television and Warner Bros.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] In 2009, 10 lost the rights to Universal Pictures after more than 20 years of movies and television broadcasting when the Seven Network won the $500 billion and long-term deal with the movie and television studio broadcast TV rights.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] Network 10's news service is called *10 News* (previously *Ten News*, *Ten Eyewitness News* and *10 News First*).
[src:seven-network/10-hd] It produces local bulletins each weeknight and national bulletins on weekday lunchtime, afternoons, late night and weekends.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] 10 has access to a sister service CBS News for international news coverage.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] During weekday overnights and Sunday mornings, Network 10 rebroadcasts American television network CBS's (sister network since 2017) morning news program *CBS Mornings*.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] In November 2006, Network 10 struck a deal with CBS, reportedly worth A$6 million a year.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] This allows Network Ten the rights to air all CBS News footage, as well as access to its *60 Minutes*, *Dr.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] Phil*, *Late Show with David Letterman* and *48 Hours* programs.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] This deal occurred after CBS's talks with the Nine Network broke down, with Nine refusing to pay A$8 million a year to continue its 40-year deal with CBS.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] Ten in turn struck a cheaper deal and has onsold CBS's 60 Minutes stories to Nine.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] On 31 July 2012, *Entertainment Tonight* was picked up by Network 10 after airing since 1982 until 30 June 2012 on the Nine Network following cutbacks on overseas purchases.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] In late 2012, 10 reported a loss of $12.9m as it battled poor advertising markets and failed to hold larger audience numbers.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] In September 2020, a major restructure of the news service saw local bulletins in Brisbane and Adelaide axed, with their bulletins being merged with their Sydney and Melbourne counterparts, respectively, and production of the Perth bulletin once again move to Sydney.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] The network is a major player in Australian sports broadcasting.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] All sports broadcasts on 10 and its multi-channels are labelled under the *10 Sport* brand.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] Since the Paramount takeover, however, the channel has significantly toned down its commitment to sports programming.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] In 2002, 10 combined with the Nine Network and Foxtel to acquire broadcast rights for the Australian Football League, the elite Australian rules competition, displacing the Seven Network which had held the rights for more than 40 years.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] 10 broadcast Saturday afternoon and Saturday night games and had exclusive rights for all finals games.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] Along with the Seven Network, 10 placed a successful $780 million bid to jointly broadcast the game from 2007 to 2011.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] Under this deal, 10 continued to broadcast the Saturday component of the competition.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] However, unlike the previous deal, 10 did not hold the exclusive rights to the finals series.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] Instead, the networks shared the broadcasting of the finals series and alternated the broadcast of the grand final.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] In the years when 10 did not televise the Grand Final (2008 and 2010), it telecast the pre-season Grand Final and the Brownlow Medal presentation.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] 10 ended AFL broadcasting after 10 years at the conclusion of the 2011 season.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] In 2003, 10 started broadcasting the Formula One World Championship after the Nine Network dropped the rights in 2002 after more than twenty years of coverage.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] All Big Bash League games were broadcast in Australia by 10.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] In 2013, 10 paid $100 million for BBL rights over five years, marking the channel's first foray in elite domestic cricket coverage.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] Ten previously held the broadcast rights to the Indian Premier League.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] 10, in joint partnership with subscription television provider Foxtel, had broadcast rights for the 2010 Commonwealth Games.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] 10 acquired broadcast rights to the 2014 Winter Olympics in Sochi, Russia for AUD$20 million after all three major commercial networks pulled out of bidding on rights to both the 2014 and 2016 Olympic Games due to cost concerns.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] The Nine Network had lost AUD$22 million on its joint coverage of the 2012 Games with Foxtel, and the Seven Network's bid was rejected for being lower than what Nine/Foxtel had previously paid.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] In 2018, 10 signed the rights to the Melbourne Cup Carnival, after the Seven Network ended the rights for 17 years.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] In 2019, 10 broadcast the 2019 Rugby World Cup.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] In 2021, 10 acquired the rights to a range of football content, most notably both A-League Men and Women competitions as well as Socceroos and Matildas games.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] The deal also included content from the AFC, which includes the AFC Champions League and other World Cup qualifiers in the AFC region involving non-Australian teams, among others.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] Football content will be broadcast across both Paramount+ and free-to-air platforms.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] Network 10 is available in standard definition and in 1080i high definition.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] Core programming is fibre fed out of ATV Melbourne to its sister stations and regional affiliates with TEN Sydney providing national news programming.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] In addition to this, 10 is retransmitted via Foxtel's cable and satellite pay television services.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] The 10 HD multichannel was launched on 16 December 2007 on channels 1 & 14 for 2 years of experience until breakaway programming.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] 10 HD ceased broadcasting on 26 March 2009 with the launch of One HD, and later revived on 2 March 2016.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] It broadcasts identical programming to 10 but in 1080i HD.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] From 2002, this was interspersed with a loop of high definition demonstration material during business hours, for viewing in the showrooms of television retailers, at the conclusion of an equivalent service by Network 10.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] After the Nine Network restarted broadcasting 9HD in November 2015, 10 confirmed that it was working on rebroadcasting 10 HD.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] However, they did not put a time frame on it, stating that they are "working through some technical and rights issues".
[src:seven-network/10-hd] On 11 February 2016, some smart TVs began receiving notification messages advising of 10 HD through a "ghost broadcast" that soon disappeared.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] 10 later recommenced simulcasting in high definition on 2 March 2016 on channel 13 from 3pm, in time for the 2016 season of the Virgin Australia Supercars Championship.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] As a result, One was reduced to a standard definition broadcast on both channel 1 and channel 12.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] 10 uses MPEG-4 technology to broadcast 10 HD.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] The network's free video on demand and catch up TV service, **10** (formerly 10Play), launched on 29 September 2013.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] It replaced the network's old website that offered limited catch-up TV services.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] In December 2022, 10 launched FAST channels on the service.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] The service is available on the web and via apps for mobile devices, smart TVs, set-top boxes and video game consoles.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] 10 All Access was launched on 4 December 2018 as an ad-free subscription streaming service.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] It was a rebranded, localised version of CBS All Access.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] The service offered programming from 10 and CBS's libraries, original programming, a Livestream of CBS News and the ability to watch select CBS programmes prior to their broadcast on 10's channels.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] It was stated that existing Paramount Plus streaming services in Latin America and Nordic Europe, as well as 10 All Access, would be migrated to the then-unnamed service.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] On 16 September 2020, it was officially announced that 10 All Access would be rebranded as Paramount+ in mid-2021.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] On 7 May 2021, it was announced that Paramount+ would launch on 11 August.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] ViacomCBS also announced that the second season of *Five Bedrooms* would premiere on Paramount Plus' launch date and that Australian original series including *Spreadsheet*, *Last King of the Cross* and movie *6 Festivals* were in production for the platform.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] In 2022, the streaming platform streamed exclusive coverage of the FA Cup in Australia and announced original series *Spreadsheet*, *The Bridge Australia* and *Couples Therapy Australia*.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] It also released teen drama *More Than This*, lifestyle factual series *Undressed* and documentary series *Sky Blue: Inside Sydney FC*.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] In 2023, Paramount+ released original series *Last King of the Cross*, *One Night*, *NCIS: Sydney*, *The Betoota Advocate Presents*, *The Inspired Unemployed (Impractical) Jokers* and movie *The Appleton Ladies' Potato Race*.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] At the start of August 2023, it was confirmed that an Australian version of Pluto TV would be launched within the existing live streaming service platform for Network 10 from the end of the month.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] The initial tranche of content announced for the new service included "box set" FAST channels for series such as *South Park*, *I Love Lucy* and *Happy Days*, alongside several MTV and Nickelodeon branded streams, such as MTV Reality, Nick Classics and Nicktoons.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] For the 2006 series of *Big Brother*, Ten appointed two censors to review the show instead of one.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] The Federal Minister for Communications, Senator Helen Coonan, was reported to have said that she would be keeping a "close watch on the show's 2006 series".
[src:seven-network/10-hd] This controversy resulted in *Big Brother Uncut* being renamed *Big Brother: Adults Only* for the 2006 season of *Big Brother*.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] In two separate findings, the Australian Communications and Media Authority determined Network Ten breached clause 2.4 of the Commercial Television Industry Code of Practice.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] These two breaches were in relation to the broadcast of *Big Brother Uncut* on 30 May, 13 June and 4 July 2005.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] The broadcast material was not classified according to the Television Classification Guidelines.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] Despite toning down *Big Brother: Adults Only* significantly in comparison to 2005, the series continued to attract controversy.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] After *Big Brother: Adults Only* was abruptly cancelled several weeks early, a subsequent incident of alleged sexual assault in the house saw the removal of two housemates and a huge public outcry calling for the series to be cancelled entirely.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] Just prior to the fifth anniversary of the 9/11 attacks, Network Ten broadcast *911: In Plane Site*, a documentary that examined conspiracy theories about the terrorist attacks.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] Federal Labor politician Michael Danby demanded that the programming director of the station be sacked.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] On 8 October 2008, the Australian Communications and Media Authority (ACMA) found Network Ten guilty of breaching the Commercial Television Industry Code of Practice by using subliminal advertising during the broadcast of the 2007 ARIA Music Awards on 28 October 2007.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] Network Ten had inserted single frames (lasting 1/25th of a second) into the program broadcast.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] This was exposed on ABC's *Media Watch* program.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] From 1964 to 1984 Network Ten's four stations – ATV-0/ATV-10 Melbourne, TEN-10 Sydney, TVQ-0 Brisbane and SAS-10 Adelaide – used different logos to identify themselves.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] There had also been a number of network-wide logos used from the mid-1960s through to the early 1980s.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] By late-1985 ATV-10, SAS-10 and TEN-10 were all using the same logo – a circle with "TEN" in the centre, somewhat in the style of a neon sign.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] This logo had been introduced by TEN-10 on 16 January 1983, was adopted by ATV-10 in June 1984 and by SAS-10 in October 1985.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] The logo was also similar to the new logo adopted by Brisbane's TVQ-0 in April 1983, when that station became branded as TV0 – a neon sign-style circle with "TV" in the centre.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] Kicking off several years of branding upheaval, on 24 January 1988 ATV-10, ADS-10 and TEN-10 all adopted the "X TEN" logo, followed by Perth's NEW-10 when the station launched in May of that year, and finally TVQ-0 on 10 September, when the station changed frequency and became TVQ-10.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] On 23 July 1989, the network rebranded again to "10 TV Australia".
[src:seven-network/10-hd] On 13 January 1991, the network introduced a new logo featuring a lowercase "ten" in a circle; four variations of this logo would appear over the next 27 years.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] The first version consisted of a white, silver or metallic ring enclosing a blue circle with "ten" in yellow lowercase text.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] A revision of the logo with a yellow ring was introduced with the "Give Me Ten" ident campaign in 1995, but the white/silver/metallic ring was reintroduced with the network's 1997 idents.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] It was not until 1 October 1999 when the "Electric" ident was launched that the ring became yellow permanently.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] On 16 December 2007, the logo was enhanced for HD with a glossy "ball" effect similar to the logo of the American network ABC.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] On 22 June 2013, the logo changed again, when the ring and lettering became blue as well.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] On 31 October 2018, Ten unveiled a completely new logo, in its first major rebranding since 1991.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] The new branding replaced the "ten" wordmark with a numeric 10 in a circle.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] On 30 June 2025, 10 simplified their logo by dropping the long-familiar circle in place of a circle-free 10 logo, previously used only sparingly across the network, as the primary logo.
[src:seven-network/10-hd] This occurred in conjunction with the rebranding of 10 Comedy and 10 Drama.
[src:seven-network/10-news] The news division also draws upon the resources of CBS News, and among non-Paramount Skydance sources, ITN (which produces 5 News UK, which is owned by Paramount), APTN and Reuters for select international coverage.
[src:seven-network/10-news] Network 10's news service was introduced on 2 August 1964 with the launch of ATV-10 in Melbourne, followed on 5 April 1965 by TEN-10 in Sydney.
[src:seven-network/10-news] The network was the first to introduce dual-anchored hour-long news bulletins in the form of *Eyewitness News* from 1973 onwards.
[src:seven-network/10-news] The 1980s were the network's most successful period as a news provider with its local Sydney, Melbourne and Brisbane bulletins often rating highest for their 6 pm timeslots.
[src:seven-network/10-news] A major change to the service occurred on 20 January 1992 when all five of its local bulletins were moved to the 5 pm time slot.
[src:seven-network/10-news] In 1994, all local weekend bulletins were axed across the network and replaced by a 30-minute network bulletin from Sydney – *Ten Weekend News*, initially presented by John Gatfield and later by Tracey Spicer, Natarsha Belling and Bill Woods.
[src:seven-network/10-news] In September 2010, the network announced a major expansion of its news service.
[src:seven-network/10-news] From 24 January 2011, It expanded its evening news output by introducing a national current affairs program at 6 pm, *6PM with George Negus* (later *6.30 with George Negus*), and an additional local bulletin at 6:30 pm on weeknights, under the *Ten Evening News* brand.
[src:seven-network/10-news] In addition, the network announced the re-introduction of local weekend bulletins at 6 pm and the axing of its 5 pm national bulletin.
[src:seven-network/10-news] Two months after the relaunch, the national weekend bulletins were re-introduced owing to poor ratings, although the 6 pm local bulletins continued to air.
[src:seven-network/10-news] Later that month, the network dropped its 6:30 pm local bulletins on weeknights, extended *Ten News at Five* to 90 minutes and moved George Negus' program to 6:30 pm each weeknight.
[src:seven-network/10-news] The changes were introduced on Monday 4 April 2011.
[src:seven-network/10-news] Further changes in September 2011 saw the axing of the network's late night bulletin and the state-based 6 pm weekend bulletins.
[src:seven-network/10-news] The 5 pm national bulletin on Saturdays and Sundays was extended to 90 minutes a month later.
[src:seven-network/10-news] Later that month, the network axed *6.30 with George Negus* and replaced it with an hour-long version of *The 7PM Project* (renamed *The Project*).
[src:seven-network/10-news] In November 2011, the last half-hour of Network 10's 5 pm state bulletins were rebranded as *Ten News at Six*.
[src:seven-network/10-news] Two months later, the main 5 pm bulletin was shortened back to 60 minutes from Sunday 22 January 2012 with *The Project* moved to 6 pm.
[src:seven-network/10-news] The network's *Ten Early News* bulletin was axed in February 2012 following the launch of Network 10's *Breakfast* program.
[src:seven-network/10-news] More changes during the year saw the return of a networked *Ten Late News* in a new format launched on 4 June 2012, and the axing of *Breakfast* on 30 November 2012, due to low ratings and cost-cutting measures at the network.
[src:seven-network/10-news] On 15 September 2013, Network 10 reintroduced the *Ten Eyewitness News* branding for all of its news output, including the flagship 5 pm state bulletins.
[src:seven-network/10-news] Two months later, a new breakfast program, *Wake Up*, was launched.
[src:seven-network/10-news] On 21 May 2014, Network 10 announced it would axe *Wake Up* and all national news bulletins on weekdays as part of a wider cost-cutting program with the loss of around 150 jobs, caused by poor ratings and advertising revenue.
[src:seven-network/10-news] The network also closed its two international bureaux in Los Angeles and London.
[src:seven-network/10-news] As of 2018, the state-based 5 pm news continues to air, alongside national bulletins at weekends.
[src:seven-network/10-news] In February 2014, Network 10 announced that Hugh Riminton would join Sandra Sully as a co-anchor of the bulletin.
[src:seven-network/10-news] In November 2014, Candice Wyatt joined Stephen Quartermain as a co-anchor and finally in August 2015 Lachlan Kennedy joined Georgina Lewis as a co-anchor in Brisbane.
[src:seven-network/10-news] On 16 May 2016, *Ten Eyewitness News* updated their set and graphics.
[src:seven-network/10-news] In January 2017, the three east coast metro bulletins (Sydney, Melbourne and Brisbane) returned to solo anchors with Hugh Riminton, Candice Wyatt and Lachlan Kennedy returning to reporting duties in February.
[src:seven-network/10-news] On 1 November 2018, alongside a major network relaunch, the *Ten Eyewitness News* branding was replaced with *10 News First*.
[src:seven-network/10-news] On 2 December 2019, the 5 pm edition of *10 News First* was extended to 90 minutes.
[src:seven-network/10-news] On 11 August 2020, 10 announced it would transfer studio presentation of the Brisbane and Perth bulletins to Sydney with the Adelaide bulletin moved to Melbourne.
[src:seven-network/10-news] Reporters, camera crews and editorial staff were retained in Adelaide, Brisbane and Perth.
[src:seven-network/10-news] An afternoon bulletin, titled *10 News First: Afternoons*, was also introduced in 2024, premiering on 29 January 2024.
[src:seven-network/10-news] On 16 June 2025, Network 10 announced it would be rebranding its news division to *10 News*, alongside the announcement of the new public affairs program named *10 News+* which premiered on 30 June 2025.
[src:seven-network/10-news] The network's first late news bulletin, *Ten Evening News: Crisis in the Gulf*, was hosted by veteran newsreader Eric Walters and was part of the network's coverage of the First Gulf War in January 1991.
[src:seven-network/10-news] The bulletin also aired on weekends, hosted by Tracey Spicer, until the Saturday and Sunday editions were axed in 2004 and 2005 respectively.
[src:seven-network/10-news] In 2006, the bulletin was merged with the late weeknight edition of *Sports Tonight* on Monday through Thursday nights.
[src:seven-network/10-news] Due to declining ratings and increased competition, the bulletin was axed with the final week of episodes hosted by Sandra Sully (news) and Brad McEwan (*Sports Tonight*) on Monday through Thursday, and Tim Webster on Friday 30 September 2011.
[src:seven-network/10-news] Sully became co-host of Sydney's evening bulletin alongside Bill Woods.
[src:seven-network/10-news] The bulletin was revived on 4 June 2012 in a new magazine-style format, hosted by Hamish Macdonald.
[src:seven-network/10-news] In September 2013, the bulletin was rebranded as *Ten Eyewitness News: Late* and Danielle Isdale replaced Macdonald after he resigned later that same month.
[src:seven-network/10-news] Hugh Riminton later replaced Isdale as host and the bulletin returned to a standard news bulletin format.
[src:seven-network/10-news] The bulletin was again axed in May 2014 alongside the early and morning news bulletins.
[src:seven-network/10-news] In 2026, the bulletin was expanded to one hour and brought forward to start at 9:30 pm.
[src:seven-network/10-news] Since 25 May 2026, sport has been presented under the *Sports Tonight* banner, as was the case between 2006–11.
[src:seven-network/10-news] This segment is presented by either Max Burford or Adrian Franklin on a rotating basis.
[src:seven-network/10-news] The weekend edition of *10 News* airs on Saturday and Sunday evenings at 5 pm and is presented from the network's Sydney studios by Georgie Tunny with sport presenter Scott Mackinnon and weather presenter Amanda Jason.
[src:seven-network/10-news] The national bulletin was introduced in 1994 to replace state-based bulletins (excluding Adelaide and Perth, who had state-based weekend bulletins until early 1996) but axed in January 2011 ahead of the reintroduction of local editions at 6 pm.
[src:seven-network/10-news] The national edition was reinstated two months later in the wake of poor ratings.
[src:seven-network/10-news] The 6 pm local bulletins continued to air until October 2011 when the 5 pm national news was extended to 90 minutes.
[src:seven-network/10-news] Until July 2014, a separate edition for Perth and Western Australia was also broadcast from the Pyrmont studios in Sydney.
[src:seven-network/10-news] Localised Sydney-produced weekend editions were restored for Perth and Western Australia by late 2018.
[src:seven-network/10-news] Then weeknight presenter Narelda Jacobs presented the Perth edition until she was reappointed to present the weeknight bulletins for Perth in September 2020; Bath would present both the national and Perth editions of the weekend news ever since.
[src:seven-network/10-news] In April 2026, the separate Perth bulletin presented on weekends moved production to Subiaco, and is presented by Jacobs.
[src:seven-network/10-news] In December 2018, it was announced that Natarsha Belling would move to *Studio 10* in 2019 to present news updates throughout the show.
[src:seven-network/10-news] In October 2025, Network 10 announced it would not renew Chris Bath's contract as part of a broader cost-cutting initiative.
[src:seven-network/10-news] She would remain with network until December.
[src:seven-network/10-news] The bulletin has previously been presented by Chris Bath, Natarsha Belling, Hermione Kitson, Mike Munro, Matt Doran, Bill Woods, Steve Liebmann, Tracey Spicer and John Gatfield.
[src:seven-network/10-news] Fill-in presenters include Hugh Riminton, Amanda Hart, Taylor Ryan, Ashleigh Raper and Tallulah Thompson (news), and Chloe-Amanda Bailey (sport).
[src:seven-network/10-news] Short, localised updates air late afternoons and early evenings by each capital city's main newsreader Monday to Friday, with national updates originating from Sydney over the weekend.
[src:seven-network/10-news] The Sydney edition is simulcast on 10 Northern NSW in Northern New South Wales and in Griffith via 10 Griffith, and across Southern New South Wales and the Australian Capital Territory via 10 Southern NSW and ACT.
[src:seven-network/10-news] Between 1995 and 2005, the bulletin was presented by Ron Wilson and Jessica Rowe, until Rowe moved to co-host *Today* on the Nine Network.
[src:seven-network/10-news] She was replaced by former US correspondent Deborah Knight in 2006.
[src:seven-network/10-news] Wilson moved to the national *Early News* bulletin, after presenting his final 5 pm Sydney bulletin as main anchor on Friday 16 January 2009.
[src:seven-network/10-news] In October 2011, Sandra Sully replaced Deborah Knight following the axing of *Ten Late News*.
[src:seven-network/10-news] Knight left the network to join the Nine Network as a *Nine News* presenter and *Weekend Today* as a news presenter.
[src:seven-network/10-news] Bill Woods left the network on 30 November 2012 after his contract was not renewed as part of cost-cutting measures.
[src:seven-network/10-news] Ron Wilson was also set to leave on the same day, however he stayed until 28 December that year as he presented his final bulletin for Ten News after being employed there for 34 years.
[src:seven-network/10-news] He then moved back to radio in April 2013 as a newsreader and radio announcer for smoothfm.
[src:seven-network/10-news] In February 2014, Hugh Riminton joined Sandra Sully as a co-anchor, but returned to reporting three years later when the bulletin returned to a solo-anchor format.
[src:seven-network/10-news] Fill-in presenters include Hugh Riminton, Ursula Heger and Georgie Tunny (news), Chloe-Amanda Bailey (sport), Taylor Ryan and Sarah Navin (weather).
[src:seven-network/10-news] The network's Melbourne news operation was originally based at the Nunawading studios until a move to the Como Centre in 1992.
[src:seven-network/10-news] Mal Walden joined ATV-10 in April 1987, shortly after his abrupt sacking by HSV-7 – he took over the weekday 5 pm bulletin in 1996 alongside Jennifer Hansen who was replaced by Helen Kapalos in 2006.
[src:seven-network/10-news] Kapalos was sacked in November 2012 amid cost-cutting measures at the network.
[src:seven-network/10-news] Walden anchored the bulletin solo until his retirement in December 2013.
[src:seven-network/10-news] George Donikian was the main male fill-in during the 2000s, including presenting the Saturday 6 pm bulletin during the 2002–11 period that Network 10 had the AFL broadcasting rights.
[src:seven-network/10-news] Sport presenter Stephen Quartermain then assumed that role, though he had filled-in as news presenter during various times in the past, when Donikian was unavailable.
[src:seven-network/10-news] Mignon Stewart (née Henne) was the main female fill-in for Jennifer Hansen and Helen Kapalos during the 2000s (including for an extended stint in early 2006 before Kapalos started).
[src:seven-network/10-news] There was no female fill-in for much of 2008 and 2009.
[src:seven-network/10-news] Hermione Kitson became the female fill-in during 2010 and moved to Sydney in 2012.
[src:seven-network/10-news] During the 2000s, occasionally due to availability and network commitments, Walden or Kapalos would present solo (particularly after major events such as the AFL Grand Final).
[src:seven-network/10-news] Traffic Reporter Vanessa O'Hanlon left after six years (2003–2008) in 2008 for *ABC News Breakfast*.
[src:seven-network/10-news] Emma Notarfrancesco left after four and a half years (2010–2015), to work for Formula 1's Australian media team on Friday 20 February 2015.
[src:seven-network/10-news] Jimmy Wirtanen then returned to the role.
[src:seven-network/10-news] In November 2014, Candice Wyatt joined Stephen Quartermain as co-anchor of the bulletin, but returned to reporting just over two years later when the bulletin returned to a solo-anchor format.
[src:seven-network/10-news] In May 2018, Network 10 announced that Jennifer Keyte would leave the Seven Network to present the bulletin replacing Stephen Quartermain, who was redeployed to his former role of presenting sport on the bulletin.
[src:seven-network/10-news] Past presenters of Network 10's Melbourne news included David Johnston, who presented the flagship evening bulletin for 16 years (alongside the likes of Jana Wendt and Jo Pearson) until his departure for HSV-7 in 1996.
[src:seven-network/10-news] The Melbourne bulletin is simulcast across most of regional Victoria via 10 Regional Victoria, to the city of Mildura via 10 Mildura, most of metropolitan and regional Tasmania via 10 TDT, the south areas of Remote and Eastern Australia via 10 Central and to the city of Darwin via 10 Darwin.
[src:seven-network/10-news] In September 2020, studio production for the Melbourne bulletin was merged with the Adelaide bulletin with opt-outs for local news, sport and weather alongside shared content; the bulletins were separated and Melbourne returned to a solo bulletin on 3 February 2023.
[src:seven-network/10-news] Fill in presenters include Jayde Cotic and Stephen Quartermain (News), Adrian Franklin and Caty Price (Sport), Steph Baumgartel and Sophie Jacobson (Weather).
[src:seven-network/10-news] The Brisbane edition is simulcast across regional Queensland via 10 Regional Queensland, the Gold Coast via 10 Northern NSW and Gold Coast and the north areas of Remote and Central Australia via 10 Central.
[src:seven-network/10-news] Reporters are also based at a remote newsroom on the Gold Coast.
[src:seven-network/10-news] In August 2015, Lachlan Kennedy joined Georgina Lewis as co-anchor of the bulletin, but returned to reporting merely eighteen months later when the bulletin returned to a solo-anchor format.
[src:seven-network/10-news] Former long-serving presenter Marie-Louise Theile left *Ten News* on 14 December 2007 to spend more time with her family.
[src:seven-network/10-news] Other previous presenters include Geoff Mullins, Tracey Spicer, Brad McEwan and Bill McDonald, who left in November 2012 when his contract was not renewed due to cost-cutting measures.
[src:seven-network/10-news] In September 2020, studio production for the Brisbane bulletin was transferred to Sydney with a single bulletin containing opt-outs of local news, sport and weather for Sydney and Brisbane alongside shared content.
[src:seven-network/10-news] Georgina Lewis, presenter of 13 years, and sports presenter Jonathan Williams were among those that were made redundant in the restructure with the final Brisbane-based bulletin broadcast on 11 September 2020.
[src:seven-network/10-news] On 15 August 2024, it was announced that a separate bulletin, presented from Ten's Mt Coot-tha studios, would be restored from 2 September 2024, with former reporter Sharyn Ghidella returning to the network after more than thirty years.
[src:seven-network/10-news] Fill in presenters include Pippa Sheehan, Georgina Hill (News), Josh McLean (Sport), Tiarni Reid and Brendan Smith (weather).
[src:seven-network/10-news] The Adelaide bulletin is simulcast to Port Lincoln, the Upper Spencer Gulf of South Australia and the city of Broken Hill in New South Wales via 10 Spencer Gulf and Broken Hill, and to the Riverland and the South East areas of South Australia via 10 South Australia.
[src:seven-network/10-news] In 2000, studio production for the 5 pm Adelaide bulletin was moved to the network's Melbourne studios in South Yarra.
[src:seven-network/10-news] The bulletin was presented from Melbourne for the next decade while sport and weather segments were still presented locally from the station's studios in North Adelaide and subsequently, from 2007, in newly-built studios in Hutt Street.
[src:seven-network/10-news] Initially, then-presenters George Donikian and Nikki Dwyer relocated from Adelaide to present the new Melbourne based bulletin.
[src:seven-network/10-news] After 8 years co-anchoring with Donikian, Dwyer eventually resigned as presenter in late 2000 after she decided to move back to Adelaide, to begin starting a family.
[src:seven-network/10-news] Dwyer was subsequently replaced as presenter by Kelly Nestor who resigned in 2006 and was succeeded by Rebecca Morse.
[src:seven-network/10-news] On 21 January 2011, George Donikian presented his final Melbourne-based bulletin for *Ten News Adelaide*.
[src:seven-network/10-news] Studio presentation subsequently returned to ADS-10's Adelaide studios on 24 January 2011, to coincide with the launch of the short-lived 6:30 pm local bulletin.
[src:seven-network/10-news] Rebecca Morse relocated with the bulletin to Adelaide while Donikian remained in Melbourne, co-presenting the Melbourne edition of *Ten News at Five* with Helen Kapalos for two months before being reduced to Fridays only, as well as presenting the localised weekend edition.
[src:seven-network/10-news] Jane Reilly retired as weather presenter in April 2013 after 37 years and was succeeded by Kate Freebairn.
[src:seven-network/10-news] A year later, Mark Aiston resigned as sport presenter.
[src:seven-network/10-news] In September 2020, studio production for the Adelaide bulletin was transferred back to Melbourne with a single bulletin containing opt-outs of local news, sport and weather for Adelaide and Melbourne alongside shared content.
[src:seven-network/10-news] Rebecca Morse, presenter of 14 years, and sports presenter Will Goodings were among those that were made redundant in the restructure with the final Adelaide-based bulletin broadcast on 11 September 2020.
[src:seven-network/10-news] In February 2022, the Adelaide newsroom was relocated to newly-built offices on Greenhill Road in Eastwood.
[src:seven-network/10-news] The Adelaide and Melbourne bulletins were separated on 3 February 2023; studio production of the Adelaide bulletin was moved to the network's Sydney studios, where Kate Freebairn is now based, to present a new solo bulletin for Adelaide.
[src:seven-network/10-news] The Perth bulletin is simulcast to most of regional Western Australia via 10 Western Australia.
[src:seven-network/10-news] Production of the Perth bulletin was initially moved to Pyrmont in 2000, citing high costs of converting the network's Dianella studios.
[src:seven-network/10-news] Then-presenters Greg Pearce and Christina Morrissy relocated to Sydney to present the bulletin, whilst sport and weather segments were still presented locally from the station's studios in Dianella.
[src:seven-network/10-news] Morrissy later resigned from these duties after suffering deep vein thrombosis on a flight and was replaced by Celina Edmonds.
[src:seven-network/10-news] Pearce also later resigned to return to Perth, while Edmonds resigned to spend more time with her family.
[src:seven-network/10-news] She then moved to Sky News Australia as a presenter and reporter.
[src:seven-network/10-news] Following their departures, Tim Webster and Charmaine Dragun became the main presenters of *Ten News Perth* from 2005.
[src:seven-network/10-news] On 18 January 2008, it was announced that studio production of *Ten News* would return to Perth.
[src:seven-network/10-news] The network denied that the move was related to the death of Charmaine Dragun as the decision to switch production had been made well beforehand.
[src:seven-network/10-news] Narelda Jacobs began presenting in the Sydney studios in May 2008 before *Ten News Perth* presentation returned to the Dianella studios on Monday 23 June 2008.
[src:seven-network/10-news] In December 2016, Network 10 moved into new offices in Subiaco, relocating from Dianella.
[src:seven-network/10-news] In December 2019, it was announced that former *Today Tonight* presenter Monika Kos would replace Jacobs as anchor from 13 January 2020 with Jacobs to move to Sydney to co-host *Studio 10*.
[src:seven-network/10-news] In September 2020, studio production for the Perth bulletin was transferred back to Sydney with Narelda Jacobs returning as anchor.
[src:seven-network/10-news] The bulletin continued to air live with sports news presented from the Perth newsroom.
[src:seven-network/10-news] On 13 March 2023, presentation of the Perth bulletin once again returned to the Subiaco studio as a trial, with Natalie Forrest as anchor.
[src:seven-network/10-news] In December 2023, it was announced that the bulletin would remain in Perth.
[src:seven-network/10-news] In 10's regional viewing areas, additional local news updates air at various times during the day and evening Monday to Friday.
[src:seven-network/10-news] Updates are produced and recorded in both Sydney (Southern NSW & ACT) and Melbourne (Regional Victoria, Regional Queensland) since January 2026, with separate updates for the local areas within each state.
[src:seven-network/10-news] Current presenters are Stacey Eldridge (Southern NSW & ACT), Sarah Bennallack (Regional Victoria), and Mae James (Regional Queensland).
[src:seven-network/10-news] These updates were previously produced in Hobart by former regional affiliate Southern Cross Austereo while transitioning from regional affiliate ownership to network ownership.
[src:seven-network/10-news] Following 10's acquisition of NRN Northern NSW & Gold Coast in May 2025, local updates currently continue to be produced and recorded in Wollongong by *WIN News* under *10 News* branding since June 2025.
[src:seven-network/10-news] The current presenters for the local updates are Keeley Hurry and Madison Arnold, with Georgia Elsley filling-in.
[src:seven-network/10-news] Updates in Tasmania are produced independently by Seven Tasmania, who co-own 10’s local affiliate TDT alongside WIN Tasmania.
[src:seven-network/10-news] Ashleigh Raper, Georgie Tunny, Carrie-Anne Greenbank, Johnpaul Gonzo and Harvey Biggs are fill-in presenters on the bulletin.
[src:seven-network/10-news] In October 2025, Network 10 announced that *10 News+* will be cut from one hour to 30 minutes from 2026.
[src:seven-network/10-news] Over the decades, Network 10 has experimented with a wide range of current affairs formats.
[src:seven-network/10-news] The network's early morning news program began as *Ten Early News* in January 2006, airing for one hour at 6 am weekday mornings and featuring a number of segments unique to its timeslot, such as morning newspaper headlines from the country's major papers.
[src:seven-network/10-news] The last edition aired on Wednesday 22 February 2012 in preparation of the earlier-than-scheduled launch of Network 10's *Breakfast* program.
[src:seven-network/10-news] The bulletin was revived on 4 November 2013 as *Ten Eyewitness News: Early*, airing from 5:30 am to 6:30 am on weekdays, immediately preceding the network's new breakfast program *Wake Up*.
[src:seven-network/10-news] The bulletin was originally presented by Bill Woods until he became a presenter for the Sydney edition of *Ten News at Five*, switching roles with Ron Wilson in January 2009.
[src:seven-network/10-news] For the revival, Hermione Kitson anchored alongside sports presenter Scott Mackinnon and weather presenter Amanda Jason.
[src:seven-network/10-news] The final edition of the early news aired on Friday 23 May 2014, when the bulletin was axed alongside *Wake Up* and the morning and late news bulletins.
[src:seven-network/10-news] Ten originally aired a late morning news program from 1980 until cost-cutting measures led to its axing ten years later.
[src:seven-network/10-news] It was revived in 1994 and presented by David Johnston from the Melbourne newsroom.
[src:seven-network/10-news] From 1994–2000 and August – December 2005, *Ten Morning News* would air after the successful *Good Morning Australia with Bert Newton*.
[src:seven-network/10-news] In 1996, Jason Cameron took over as presenter for the next four years until production was moved to 10's Pyrmont news centre in Sydney, where the bulletin was hosted by Tracey Spicer and Natarsha Belling.
[src:seven-network/10-news] In 2004, the bulletin briefly moved to midday (then called *Ten News at Noon*) to compete against the Australian Broadcasting Corporation's own *World at Noon* – a decision which proved unpopular.
[src:seven-network/10-news] In 2007, after Tracey Spicer left the network the previous year, Natarsha Belling became the face of the bulletin and continued the role right through to the start of 2012.
[src:seven-network/10-news] During 2010 and 2011, the bulletin aired for one hour at 9 am, before *The Circle*.
[src:seven-network/10-news] The bulletin was retired with the launch of *Breakfast* but returned upon the axing of *The Circle* in late August 2012, this time airing at 10 am on weekdays, presented by Ron Wilson.
[src:seven-network/10-news] Another round of cost-cutting measures led to the morning news being axed again on Friday 23 May 2014, alongside *Wake Up* and the early and late news bulletins.
[src:seven-network/10-news] On 9 December 2025, it was announced that the bulletin would not return in 2026.
[src:seven-network/1080i] In TV streaming, high-definition television (HDTV) and video display technology, **1080i** is a video display format with 1080 lines of vertical resolution and interlaced scanning method.
[src:seven-network/1080i] This format was once a standard in HDTV.
[src:seven-network/1080i] It was particularly used for broadcast television because it can deliver high-resolution images without needing excessive bandwidth.
[src:seven-network/1080i] This format is used in the SMPTE 292M standard.
[src:seven-network/1080i] The number "1080" in 1080i refers to the number of horizontal lines that make up the vertical resolution of the display.
[src:seven-network/1080i] Each of these lines contributes to the overall detail and clarity of the image.
[src:seven-network/1080i] This is a technique where the image is not displayed all at once.
[src:seven-network/1080i] Instead, the frame is split into two fields.
[src:seven-network/1080i] One field contains the odd-numbered lines, and the other field contains the even-numbered lines.
[src:seven-network/1080i] These fields are displayed in rapid succession, giving the appearance of a full image to the human eye.
[src:seven-network/1080i] The interlacing technique was developed to improve the motion portrayal of images without doubling the required bandwidth.
[src:seven-network/1080i] This is particularly useful in broadcasting, where bandwidth efficiency is crucial.
[src:seven-network/1080i] The frame rate is typically 50 or 60 fields per second, depending on the region.
[src:seven-network/1080i] This effectively means 25 or 30 frames per second when the fields are combined.
[src:seven-network/1080i] A key difference between 1080i and 1080p is how the lines of resolution are displayed.
[src:seven-network/1080i] Both offer 1920x1080 pixels, but the display method is different.
[src:seven-network/1080i] In 1080p, the "p" stands for progressive scan.
[src:seven-network/1080i] Each frame is drawn line by line, from top to bottom, creating a complete image in a single pass.
[src:seven-network/1080i] This results in a sharper and more stable picture, especially in fast-moving scenes.
[src:seven-network/1080i] On the other hand, 1080i uses an interlaced method.
[src:seven-network/1080i] The two fields that make up a frame are captured at slightly different times, leading to a misalignment in fast-moving parts of the image.
[src:seven-network/1080i] This can cause artifacts like "combing," where fast-moving objects appear to have a serrated edge.
[src:seven-network/1080i] However, 1080i has been preferred in broadcast television due to its lower bandwidth requirements, making it more efficient for over-the-air or cable transmission.
[src:seven-network/1080i] The origins of 1080i can be traced from Multiple sub-Nyquist sampling encoding, a Japanese analog high-definition television system.
[src:seven-network/1080i] 1080i emerged as a leading standard for HDTV broadcasts.
[src:seven-network/1080i] The ATSC (Advanced Television Systems Committee) standards and the DVB (Digital Video Broadcasting) standards allowed for the transmission of 1080i video signals.
[src:seven-network/1080i] The adoption of 1080i was particularly significant in sports broadcasting.
[src:seven-network/1080i] The higher resolution allowed for more detail and clarity, especially in large stadium shots and fast-paced action.
[src:seven-network/1080i] The format's efficiency in utilizing available bandwidth made it a practical choice for broadcasters.
[src:seven-network/1080i] However, it required more complex processing on the receiving end to deinterlace the image for display on progressive-scan screens.
[src:seven-network/1080i] Overall, 1080i played a crucial role in the early days of HDTV.
[src:seven-network/1080i] It bridged the gap between standard-definition broadcasts and the high-definition future that would soon become the norm.
[src:seven-network/1080i] While its use has diminished with the rise of 1080p and 4K resolutions, 1080i remains an important milestone in the evolution of television technology.
[src:seven-network/1080i] This means that each video frame has 1,920 pixels horizontally and 1,080 pixels vertically.
[src:seven-network/1080i] This results in over two million individual pixels per frame.
[src:seven-network/1080i] This high resolution is why 1080i is called "high-definition".
[src:seven-network/1080i] It offers a significant improvement over standard-definition formats, which typically have much lower pixel counts.
[src:seven-network/1080i] The 1920x1080 resolution allows for greater detail and clarity in images.
[src:seven-network/1080i] This makes it ideal for larger screens where higher pixel density is essential to maintain image quality.
[src:seven-network/1080i] The increased resolution is particularly noticeable in fine details such as textures, text, and intricate patterns.
[src:seven-network/1080i] These can be rendered with much greater accuracy than in lower-resolution formats.
[src:seven-network/1080i] This refers to how each video frame is displayed.
[src:seven-network/1080i] Instead of showing the entire frame at once, the interlacing technique divides each frame into two separate fields.
[src:seven-network/1080i] The first field contains all the odd-numbered lines (1, 3, 5, etc.), and the second field contains all the even-numbered lines (2, 4, 6, etc.).
[src:seven-network/1080i] These two fields are displayed one after the other.
[src:seven-network/1080i] The odd lines are shown first, followed by the even lines.
[src:seven-network/1080i] This happens very quickly, around 50 or 60 fields per second.
[src:seven-network/1080i] The human eye sees these two fields as a single, continuous image.
[src:seven-network/1080i] The main advantage of interlacing is that it allows for a higher frame rate without needing more bandwidth.
[src:seven-network/1080i] This results in smoother motion, especially for content with moderate to fast movement, like sports broadcasts.
[src:seven-network/1080i] However, interlacing also has some drawbacks.
[src:seven-network/1080i] Since the two fields are captured at slightly different times, fast-moving objects can appear misaligned between the two fields.
[src:seven-network/1080i] This creates a visual artifact called "combing." This can reduce image quality, especially in scenes with a lot of motion.
[src:seven-network/1080i] Modern display devices often use deinterlacing algorithms to combine the two fields into a single progressive image before displaying it.
[src:seven-network/1080i] The frame rate of 1080i is usually 50 or 60 Hz.
[src:seven-network/1080i] In areas using the PAL or SECAM standards, like Europe and parts of Asia, the frame rate is 50 Hz.
[src:seven-network/1080i] In regions using NTSC, like North America and Japan, the frame rate is 60 Hz.
[src:seven-network/1080i] The frame rate refers to how often a new field is shown per second.
[src:seven-network/1080i] At 50 Hz, 50 fields are shown each second.
[src:seven-network/1080i] This results in 25 full frames per second when the odd and even fields are combined.
[src:seven-network/1080i] At 60 Hz, 59.94 fields are shown per second.
[src:seven-network/1080i] This results in 29.97 full frames per second.
[src:seven-network/1080i] Interlacing affects how motion is perceived in 1080i.
[src:seven-network/1080i] Since each field represents a slightly different moment in time, motion can appear smoother compared to lower frame rate progressive scans.
[src:seven-network/1080i] However, this also means 1080i can struggle with fast-moving scenes.
[src:seven-network/1080i] The interlaced fields might not perfectly align, leading to motion artifacts.
[src:seven-network/1080i] The European Broadcasting Union (EBU) prefers to use the resolution and *frame rate* (not field rate) separated by a slash, as in *1080i/29.97* and *1080i/25*, likewise 480i/29.97 and 576i/25.
[src:seven-network/1080i] The 1080i video signals can be carried by four main digital television broadcast systems: ATSC, DVB, ISDB and DTMB.
[src:seven-network/1080i] In both ATSC and DVB systems, the 1080i signal is compressed using codecs like MPEG-2 or H.264 to reduce the bandwidth required for transmission.
[src:seven-network/1080i] In the United States, 1080i is the preferred format for most broadcasters, with Warner Bros.
[src:seven-network/1080i] Discovery, Paramount Global, and Comcast owned networks broadcasting in the format, along with most smaller broadcasters.
[src:seven-network/1080i] Only Fox- and Disney-owned television networks, along with MLB Network and a few other cable networks, use 720p as the preferred format for their networks; A&E Networks channels converted from 720p to 1080i sometime in 2013 due to acquired networks already transmitting in the 1080i format.
[src:seven-network/1080i] This also allows local newscasts on these ABC affiliates to be produced in the higher resolution (especially for weather forecasting presentation purposes for map clarity) to match the picture quality of their 1080i competitors.
[src:seven-network/1080i] Motion pictures shot on film to fit a 16:9 widescreen format (1.78:1) are typically intended to be played back at 24 frames per second.
[src:seven-network/1080i] When telecined and played back at the PAL standard 25 frames per second, films run 4.16% faster than the original, and 4.27083% faster than the NTSC film standard 23.976023976 frames per second.
[src:seven-network/1080i] High-definition television (HDTV) broadcast standards utilize 1080i (interlaced) or 720p (progressive) formats, typically offering 1920x1080 resolution.
[src:seven-network/1080i] Key, region-specific formats include 1080i25 for PAL (50 fields/second), 1080i30 for NTSC (60 fields/second), and 1080i24 for film, often converted via telecine for 25/30 frames per second, 1080i50/60 broadcasts.
[src:seven-network/1080i] PAL speed-up does not occur on footage intended for playback at 25 frames per second.
[src:seven-network/1980-summer-olympics] The **1980 Summer Olympics** (Russian: Летние Олимпийские игры 1980, romanized: *Letniye Olimpiyskiye igry 1980*), officially branded as **Moscow 1980** (Москва 1980, *Moskva 1980*), were an international multi-sport event held from 19 July to 3 August 1980 in Moscow, Russian SFSR, Soviet Union.
[src:seven-network/1980-summer-olympics] The games were the first to be staged in an Eastern Bloc country.
[src:seven-network/1980-summer-olympics] They were also the only Summer Olympic Games to be held in a communist state until the 2008 Summer Olympics held in China.
[src:seven-network/1980-summer-olympics] These were the final Olympic Games under the IOC Presidency of Michael Morris, 3rd Baron Killanin before he was succeeded by Juan Antonio Samaranch shortly afterward.
[src:seven-network/1980-summer-olympics] Eighty nations were represented at the Moscow Games, the smallest number since 1956.
[src:seven-network/1980-summer-olympics] Led by the United States, 66 countries boycotted the games entirely, because of the Soviet–Afghan War.
[src:seven-network/1980-summer-olympics] Several alternative events were held outside of the Soviet Union.
[src:seven-network/1980-summer-olympics] Some athletes from some of the boycotting countries (not included in the list of 66 countries that boycotted the games entirely) participated in the games under the Olympic Flag.
[src:seven-network/1980-summer-olympics] The Soviet Union later boycotted the 1984 Summer Olympics in Los Angeles.
[src:seven-network/1980-summer-olympics] The Soviet Union won the most gold and overall medals, with the USSR and East Germany winning 127 out of 203 available golds.
[src:seven-network/1980-summer-olympics] The only two cities to bid for the 1980 Summer Olympics were Moscow and Los Angeles.
[src:seven-network/1980-summer-olympics] The choice between them was made at the 75th IOC Session in Vienna, Austria on 23 October 1974.
[src:seven-network/1980-summer-olympics] Los Angeles would eventually host the 1984 Summer Olympics.
[src:seven-network/1980-summer-olympics] Eighty nations were represented at the Moscow Olympics, the smallest number since 1956.
[src:seven-network/1980-summer-olympics] Of the eighty participating nations, seven National Olympic Committees made their first appearance at these Games: Angola, Botswana, Cyprus, Jordan, Laos, Mozambique and Seychelles.
[src:seven-network/1980-summer-olympics] It was also the first time Vietnam participated after the end of the Vietnam War and the Reunification of Vietnam.
[src:seven-network/1980-summer-olympics] 29 countries boycotted the previous 1976 Summer Olympics in protest against the IOC for not expelling New Zealand, which had sanctioned a rugby tour of apartheid South Africa.
[src:seven-network/1980-summer-olympics] The 1980 Summer Olympics were disrupted by another, even larger, boycott led by the United States in protest of the 1979 Soviet–Afghan War.
[src:seven-network/1980-summer-olympics] The Soviet invasion spurred President Jimmy Carter to issue an ultimatum on 20 January 1980, which stated that the U.S. would boycott the Moscow Olympics if Soviet troops did not withdraw from Afghanistan within one month.
[src:seven-network/1980-summer-olympics] 66 countries and regions invited did not participate in the 1980 Olympics.
[src:seven-network/1980-summer-olympics] Many of these followed the United States' boycott initiative, while others cited economic reasons for not participating.
[src:seven-network/1980-summer-olympics] Iran, under Ayatollah Khomeini hostile to both superpowers, boycotted when the Islamic Conference condemned the invasion.
[src:seven-network/1980-summer-olympics] Neither the People's Republic of China nor Taiwan (Republic of China) participated in the games, the former as a consequence of the Sino-Soviet split.
[src:seven-network/1980-summer-olympics] Many of the boycotting nations participated instead in the Liberty Bell Classic, also known as the "Olympic Boycott Games", in Philadelphia.
[src:seven-network/1980-summer-olympics] Those that competed had won 71 percent of all medals and gold medals at the 1976 Summer Olympics in Montreal.
[src:seven-network/1980-summer-olympics] This was in part due to state-run doping programs that had been developed in the Eastern Bloc countries.
[src:seven-network/1980-summer-olympics] As a form of protest against the Soviet intervention in Afghanistan, fifteen countries marched in the Opening Ceremony with the Olympic Flag instead of their national flags, and the Olympic Flag and Olympic Hymn were used at medal ceremonies when athletes from these countries won medals.
[src:seven-network/1980-summer-olympics] Competitors from New Zealand, Portugal, and Spain competed under the flags of their respective National Olympic Committees.
[src:seven-network/1980-summer-olympics] Some of these teams that marched under flags other than their national flags were depleted by boycotts by individual athletes, while some athletes did not participate in the march.
[src:seven-network/1980-summer-olympics] The boycott impacted the competitiveness of swimming, track and field, boxing, basketball, diving, field hockey and equestrian sports.
[src:seven-network/1980-summer-olympics] Whilst competitors from 36 countries became Olympic medalists, the great majority of the medals were taken by the Soviet Union and East Germany in what was the most skewed medal tally since 1904.
[src:seven-network/1980-summer-olympics] There were 203 events – more than at any previous Olympics.
[src:seven-network/1980-summer-olympics] 36 world records, 39 European records and 74 Olympic records were set at the games.
[src:seven-network/1980-summer-olympics] In total, this was more records than were set at Montreal.
[src:seven-network/1980-summer-olympics] New Olympic records were set 241 times over the course of the competitions and world records were beaten 97 times.
[src:seven-network/1980-summer-olympics] Though no athletes were caught doping at the 1980 Summer Olympics, it has been revealed that athletes had begun using testosterone and other drugs for which tests had not been yet developed.
[src:seven-network/1980-summer-olympics] According to British journalist Andrew Jennings, a KGB colonel stated that the agency's officers had posed as anti-doping authorities from the International Olympic Committee (IOC) to undermine doping tests and that Soviet athletes were "rescued with [these] tremendous efforts".
[src:seven-network/1980-summer-olympics] A member of the IOC Medical Commission, Manfred Donike, privately ran additional tests with a new technique for identifying abnormal levels of testosterone by measuring its ratio to epitestosterone in urine.
[src:seven-network/1980-summer-olympics] Twenty percent of the specimens he tested, including those from sixteen gold medalists would have resulted in disciplinary proceedings had the tests been official.
[src:seven-network/1980-summer-olympics] The results of Donike's unofficial tests later convinced the IOC to add his new technique to their testing protocols.
[src:seven-network/1980-summer-olympics] The first documented case of "blood doping" occurred at the 1980 Summer Olympics as a runner was transfused with two pints of blood before winning medals in the 5000 m and 10,000 m.
[src:seven-network/1980-summer-olympics] Major broadcasters of the 1980 Games were USSR State TV and Radio (1,370 accreditation cards), Eurovision (31 countries, 818 cards) and Intervision (11 countries, 342 cards).
[src:seven-network/1980-summer-olympics] TV Asahi with 68 cards provided coverage for Japan, while OTI, representing Latin America, received 59 cards, and the Seven Network provided coverage for Australia (48 cards).
[src:seven-network/1980-summer-olympics] NBC, which had intended to be another major broadcaster, canceled its coverage in response to the U.S. boycott of the 1980 Games, and became a minor broadcaster with 56 accreditation cards, although they did air highlights and recaps of the Games on a regular basis.
[src:seven-network/1980-summer-olympics] ABC aired scenes of the opening ceremony during its *Nightline* program, and promised highlights each night, but later announced that they could not air any highlights as NBC still had exclusive broadcast rights in the US.
[src:seven-network/1980-summer-olympics] The Canadian Broadcasting Corporation (CBC) almost canceled their plans for coverage after Canada took part in the boycott, and was represented by nine cards.
[src:seven-network/1980-summer-olympics] The television center used 20 television channels, compared to 16 for the Montreal Games, 12 for the Munich Games, and seven for the Mexico City Games.
[src:seven-network/1980-summer-olympics] This was also the first time North Korea was watching, as KCTV (Korea Central Television) broadcast it as their first satellite program.
[src:seven-network/1980-summer-olympics] A series of commemorative coins was released in the USSR in 1977–1980 to commemorate the event.
[src:seven-network/1980-summer-olympics] It consisted of five platinum coins, six gold coins, 28 silver coins and six copper-nickel coins.
[src:seven-network/1980-summer-olympics] According to the Official Report, submitted to the IOC by the NOC of the USSR, total expenditures for the preparations for and staging of the 1980 Games were US$1,350,000,000, total revenues being US$231,000,000.
[src:seven-network/1980-summer-olympics] To obtain additional funds for the competition, the Organizing Committee organized Olympic lotteries.
[src:seven-network/1980-summer-olympics] The proceeds from the lotteries covered 25% of the cost of holding the competition.
[src:seven-network/1980-summer-olympics] Because of the U.S. boycott, changes were made to the traditional elements of the closing ceremony that represent the handover to the host city of the next Summer Olympics in Los Angeles.
[src:seven-network/1980-summer-olympics] Among them, the flag of the city of Los Angeles instead of the United States flag was raised, and the Olympic Anthem instead of the national anthem of the United States was played.
[src:seven-network/1980-summer-olympics] There was also no "Antwerp Ceremony", where the ceremonial Olympic flag was transferred from the Mayor of Moscow to the Mayor of Los Angeles; instead the flag was kept by the Moscow city authorities until 1984.
[src:seven-network/1980-summer-olympics] Furthermore, there was no next host city presentation.
[src:seven-network/1980-summer-olympics] Both the opening and closing ceremonies were shown in Yuri Ozerov's 1981 film *Oh, Sport – You Are The World!* (Russian: О спорт, ты – мир!).
[src:seven-network/1980-summer-olympics] 1 New facilities constructed in preparation for the Olympic Games.
[src:seven-network/1980-summer-olympics] 2 Existing facilities modified or refurbished in preparation for the Olympic Games.
[src:seven-network/1980-summer-olympics] This is a list of all nations that won medals at the 1980 Games.
[src:seven-network/1980-summer-olympics] In the following list, the number in parentheses indicates the number of athletes from each nation that competed in Moscow.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] The **2000 Summer Olympics**, officially the **Games of the XXVII Olympiad**, officially branded as **Sydney 2000**, and also known as the **Games of the New Millennium**, were an international multi-sport event held from 15 September to 1 October 2000 in Sydney, New South Wales, Australia.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] It marked the second time the Summer Olympics were held in Australia, and in the Southern Hemisphere, the first being in Melbourne, in 1956.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] Teams from 199 countries participated in the 2000 Games, which were the first to feature at least 300 events in its official sports program.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] The Games were estimated to have cost A$6.6 billion.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] These were the final Olympic Games under the IOC presidency of Juan Antonio Samaranch before the arrival of his successor Jacques Rogge.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] The final medal tally at the 2000 Summer Olympics was led by the United States, followed by Russia and China with host Australia in fourth place overall.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] Cameroon, Colombia, Latvia, Mozambique, and Slovenia won a gold medal for the first time in their Olympic histories, while Barbados, Kuwait, Kyrgyzstan, Macedonia, Saudi Arabia, and Vietnam won their first-ever Olympic medals.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] The 2000 Games received universal acclaim, with the organisation, volunteers, sportsmanship, and Australian public being lauded in the international media.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] Bill Bryson of *The Times* called the Sydney Games "one of the most successful events on the world stage", saying that they "couldn't be better".
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] James Mossop of the *Electronic Telegraph* called the Games "such a success that any city considering bidding for future Olympics must be wondering how it can reach the standards set by Sydney", while Jack Todd of the *Montreal Gazette* suggested that the "IOC should quit while it's ahead.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] Admit there can never be a better Olympic Games, and be done with it," as "Sydney was both exceptional and the best".
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] Australia will host the Summer Olympics in Brisbane in 2032, making it the first Asia-Pacific country to host the Summer Olympics three times.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] Sydney won the right to host the Games on 24 September 1993, after being selected over Beijing, Berlin, Istanbul, and Manchester in four rounds of voting, at the 101st IOC Session in Monte Carlo, Monaco.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] Beijing would later be selected to host the 2008 Summer Olympics eight years later on 13 July 2001 and the 2022 Winter Olympics twenty-two years later on 31 July 2015.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] Brasília, Milan, and Tashkent made bids before deciding to withdraw during the bidding process.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] Milan would later be selected to host the 2026 Winter Olympics along with Cortina d'Ampezzo twenty-six years later on 24 June 2019.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] The *Oxford Olympics Study 2016* estimates the outturn cost of the Sydney 2000 Summer Olympics at US$5 billion in 2015 dollars and cost overrun at 90% in real terms.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] Indirect capital costs are *not* included, such as for road, rail, airport infrastructure, hotel upgrades, or other business investments incurred in preparation for the Games but not directly related to staging the Games.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] The cost for Sydney 2000 compares with a cost of US$4.6 billion for Rio 2016, US$40‍–‍44 billion for Beijing 2008, and US$51 billion for Sochi 2014, the most expensive Olympics in history.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] The average cost for the Summer Games since 1960 is US$5.2 billion, average cost overrun is 176%.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] In 2000, the Auditor-General of New South Wales reported that the Sydney Games cost A$6.6 billion, with a net cost to the public between A$1.7 and A$2.4 billion.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] In the years leading up to the Games, funds were shifted from education and health programs to cover Olympic expenses.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] It has been estimated that the economic impact of the 2000 Olympics was that A$2.1 billion has been shaved from public consumption.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] Economic growth was not stimulated to a net benefit, and, in the years after 2000, foreign tourism to NSW grew by less than tourism to Australia as a whole.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] A "multiplier" effect on broader economic development was not realised, as a simple "multiplier" analysis fails to capture that resources have to be redirected from elsewhere: the building of a stadium is at the expense of other public works such as extensions to hospitals.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] Many venues that were constructed in Sydney Olympic Park failed financially in the years immediately following the Olympics to meet the expected bookings to meet upkeep expenses.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] It was only the 2003 Rugby World Cup that reconnected the park back to citizens.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] In recent years, infrastructure costs for some facilities have been of growing concern to the NSW Government, especially facilities in Western Sydney.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] Proposed metro and light rail links from Olympic Park to Parramatta have been estimated to cost in the same order of magnitude as the public expenditure on the Games.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] Stadium Australia had been considered for demolition in 2017 by then NSW Premier Gladys Berejiklian, citing that the stadium was "built for an Olympics" but not for modern spectators.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] The plan was scrapped in 2020 during the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] The Dunc Gray Velodrome has also struggled to keep up its $500,000-per-year maintenance costs, although it is still used for track cycling events.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] Although the Opening Ceremony was not scheduled until 15 September, the football competitions began with preliminary matches on 13 September.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] Among the pre-ceremony fixtures, host nation Australia lost 1‍–‍0 to Italy at the Melbourne Cricket Ground, which was the main stadium for the 1956 Melbourne Olympics.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] The opening ceremony began with a tribute to the pastoral heritage of the Australian stockmen and the importance of the stock horse in Australia's heritage.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] It was produced and filmed by the Sydney Olympic Broadcasting Organisation and the home nation broadcaster Seven Network.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] This was introduced by lone rider Steve Jefferys and his rearing Australian stock horse "Ammo".
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] At the cracking of Jefferys' stockwhip, a further 120 riders entered the stadium, their stock horses performing intricate steps, including forming the five Olympic Rings, sounded by a new version of the song that Bruce Rowland had previously composed for the 1982 film *The Man from Snowy River*.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] The Australian National Anthem was sung in the first verse by Human Nature and the second by Julie Anthony.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] The cultural segments of the event take place with many aspects of the land and its people: the affinity of the mainly coastal-dwelling Australians with the sea that surrounds the Island Continent.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] The indigenous inhabitation of the land, the coming of the First Fleet, the continued immigration from many nations, and the rural industry on which the economy of the nation was built, including a display representing the harshness of rural life based on the paintings of Sir Sidney Nolan.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] Two memorable scenes were the representation of the heart of the country by 200 Aboriginal women from Central Australia who danced up "the mighty spirit of god to protect the Games" and the overwhelmingly noisy representation of the construction industry by hundreds of tap-dancing teenagers.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] A record 199 nations entered the stadium, with a record 80 of them winning at least one medal.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] The only missing IOC member was Afghanistan, which was banned due to the extremist rule of the Taliban's oppression of women and its prohibition of sports.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] The ceremony featured a unified entrance by the athletes of North and South Korea, using a specially designed unification flag: a white background flag with a blue map of the Korean Peninsula.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] Four athletes from East Timor also marched in the parade of nations as individual Olympic athletes and marched directly before the host country.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] Although the country-to-be had no National Olympic Committee then, they were allowed to compete under the Olympic Flag with country code IOA.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] The Governor-General, Sir William Deane, opened the games.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] The Olympic Flag was carried around the arena by eight former Australian Olympic champions: Bill Roycroft, Murray Rose, Liane Tooth, Gillian Rolton, Marjorie Jackson, Lorraine Crapp, Michael Wenden and Nick Green.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] During the raising of the Olympics Flag, the Olympic Hymn was sung by the Millennium Choir of the Greek Orthodox Archdiocese of Australia in Greek.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] Following this, Tina Arena sang a purpose-written pop song, *The Flame*.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] The opening ceremony concluded with the lighting of the Olympic Flame, which was brought into the stadium by former Australian Olympic champion Herb Elliott.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] The choice of Freeman, an Aboriginal woman, to light the flame was notable given the history of human rights abuses against Aboriginal people in Australia.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] Following her lighting, Freeman was the subject of racial abuse from some Australians.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] The planned spectacular climax to the ceremony was delayed by the technical glitch of a computer switch which malfunctioned, causing the sequence to shut down by giving a false reading.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] This meant that the Olympic flame was suspended in mid-air for about four minutes rather than immediately rising up a water-covered ramp to the top of the stadium.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] When the cause of the problem was discovered, the program was overridden and the cauldron continued its course, and the ceremony concluded with a fireworks display.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] The first medals of the Games were awarded in the women's 10-metre air rifle competition, which was won by Nancy Johnson of the United States.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] The triathlon made its Olympic debut with the women's race.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] Set in the surroundings of the Sydney Opera House, Brigitte McMahon representing Switzerland swam, cycled and ran to the first gold medal in the sport, beating the favoured home athletes such as Michelie Jones who won silver.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] McMahon only passed Jones in sight of the finish line.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] The first star of the Games was 17-year-old Australian Ian Thorpe, who first set a new world record in the 400-metre freestyle final before competing in an exciting 4 × 100 m freestyle final.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] Swimming the last leg, Thorpe passed the leading American team and arrived in a new world record time, two-tenths of a second ahead of the Americans.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] In the same event for women, the Americans also broke the world record, finishing ahead of the Netherlands and Sweden.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] Samaranch had to leave for home, as his wife was severely ill.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] Upon arrival, his wife had already died.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] Samaranch returned to Sydney four days later.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] The Olympic flag was flown at half-staff during the period as a sign of respect to Samaranch's wife.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] Canadian Simon Whitfield sprinted away in the last 100 metres of the men's triathlon, becoming the inaugural winner in the event.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] On the cycling track, Robert Bartko beat fellow German Jens Lehmann in the individual pursuit, setting a new Olympic Record.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] Leontien Zijlaard-van Moorsel set a world record in the semi-finals the same event for women.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] In the swimming pool, American Tom Dolan beat the world record in the 400-metre medley, successfully defending the title he won in Atlanta four years prior.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] Dutchwoman Inge de Bruijn also clocked a new world record, beating her own time in the 100 m butterfly final to win by more than a second.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] The main event for the Australians on the fourth day of the Games was the 200 m freestyle.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] Dutchman Pieter van den Hoogenband had broken the world record in the semi-finals, taking it from the new Australian hero Ian Thorpe, who came close to the world record in his semi-final heat.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] As the final race finished, Van den Hoogenband's time was exactly the same as in the semi-finals, finishing ahead of Thorpe by half a second.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] China won the gold medal in the men's team all-around gymnastics competition after being the runner-up in the previous two Olympics.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] The other medals were taken by Ukraine and Russia, respectively.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] Zijlaard-van Moorsel lived up to the expectations set by her world record in cycling in the semis by winning the gold medal.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] During the Women's Gymnastics All-Around, female athletes suffered damning scores and injuries due to improperly installed gymnastics equipment.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] Gymnasts performing on the vault gave uncharacteristically poor performances and fell.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] Officials blamed the series of falls and low scores on performance anxiety.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] It was not until Australian gymnast Allana Slater and her coach, Peggy Liddick, voiced concerns about the equipment that officials discovered the apparatus was five centimetres, or almost two inches, lower than it should have been.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] While athletes were given the opportunity to perform again, for some of them, the damage to their mental or physical health caused by the vault was irreparable.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] Chinese gymnast Kui Yuanyuan and American gymnast Kristen Maloney both injured their legs while attempting to stick their landings, with Kui needing to be carried to an examination area and Maloney damaging a titanium rod that had recently been implanted in her shin.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] Romanian gymnast Andreea Răducan ultimately took gold while her teammates, Simona Amânar and Maria Olaru took silver and bronze, respectively.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] By rowing in the winning coxless four, Steve Redgrave of Great Britain became a member of a select group who had won gold medals at five consecutive Olympics.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] The swimming 4 x 100-metre medley relay of B.J.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] Bedford, Megan Quann (Jendrick), Jenny Thompson and Dara Torres became the first women's relay team to finish in under four minutes, swimming 3:58 and setting a world record, claiming the gold medal for the United States.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] Rulon Gardner, never an NCAA champion or a world medalist, beat Alexander Karelin of Russia to win gold in the super heavyweight class, Greco-Roman wrestling.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] Karelin had won gold in Seoul, Barcelona and Atlanta.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] Before this fight, he had never lost in international competition, had been unbeaten in all competitions in thirteen years, and had not surrendered a point in a decade.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] Australian Cathy Freeman won the 400-metre final in front of a jubilant Sydney crowd at the Olympic Stadium, ahead of Lorraine Graham of Jamaica and Katharine Merry of Great Britain.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] Freeman's win made her the first competitor in Olympic Games history to light the Olympic Flame and then go on to win a gold medal.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] The attendance at the stadium was 112,524 – the largest attendance for any sport in Olympic Games history.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] In a men's basketball pool match between the United States and France, the USA's Vince Carter made one of the most famous dunks in basketball history.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] After getting the ball off a steal, the 6'6"/1.98 m Carter drove to the basket, with 7'2"/2.18 m centre Frédéric Weis in his way.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] Carter jumped, spread his legs in midair, scraped Weis' head on the way up, and dunked.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] The French media dubbed the feat *le dunk de la mort* ("the dunk of death").
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] The Canadian flag at the athletes' village was lowered to half-mast, as Canadian athletes paid tribute to the former prime minister Pierre Trudeau after hearing of his death in Montreal (because of the time zone difference, it was 29 September in Sydney when Trudeau died).
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] The Canadian flag was flown at half-mast for the remainder of the Olympics, on orders from both IOC President Juan Antonio Samaranch and Canadian Foreign Affairs Minister Lloyd Axworthy.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] The state funeral took place on 3 October, two days after the closing ceremony, allowing enough time for those concerned to head back to Canada after the Games and attend his funeral.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] Cameroon won a historic gold medal over Spain in the Men's Olympic Football Final at the Olympic Stadium.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] The game went to a penalty shootout, which was won by Cameroon 5‍–‍3.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] The last event of the Games was the Men's Marathon, contested on a course that started in North Sydney.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] The event was won by Ethiopian Gezahegne Abera, with Kenyan Erick Wainaina second, and Tesfaye Tola, also of Ethiopia, third.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] It was the first time since the 1968 Olympics that an Ethiopian won the gold medal in this event.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] The closing ceremony commenced with Christine Anu performing her version of the Warumpi Band's song "My Island Home", with several Aboriginal dancers atop the Geodome Stage in the middle of the stadium, around which several hundred umbrella and lamp box kids created an image of Aboriginal Dreamtime.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] The Geodome Stage was used throughout the ceremony, which was a flat stage mechanically raised into the shape of a geode.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] Although demonstration sports were abolished following the 1992 Summer Olympics, the Sydney Olympics featured wheelchair racing as exhibition events on the athletics schedule.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] Special quarantine conditions were introduced to allow entry of horses into Australia to participate in equestrian events, avoiding the need for such events to take place elsewhere as had happened at the 1956 Summer Olympics in Melbourne.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] 199 National Olympic Committees (NOCs) participated in the Sydney Games, two more than in the 1996 Summer Olympics; in addition, there were four Timorese Individual Olympic Athletes.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] Eritrea, the Federated States of Micronesia and Palau made their Olympic debut this year.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] Democratic Republic of the Congo was once again designated under that name, after it participated as Zaire from 1984 to 1996.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] Afghanistan was the only 1996 participant (and the only existing NOC) that did not participate in the 2000 Olympics, having been banned due to the Taliban's totalitarian rule in Afghanistan, their oppression of women, and its prohibition of sports.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] 10,647 athletes from 199 NOCs participated in the 2000 Summer Olympics.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] These are the top ten nations that won medals in the 2000 Games.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] The ranking in this table is based on information provided by the International Olympic Committee.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] Some other sources may be inconsistent due to not taking into account all later doping cases.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] A number of quasi-government bodies were responsible for the construction, organisation and execution of the Sydney Games.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] These bodies are often collectively referred to as the "Olympic Family".
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] The organisation of the 2000 Summer Paralympics was the responsibility of the Sydney Paralympic Organising Committee (SPOC).
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] However, much of the planning and operation of the Paralympic Games was outsourced to SOCOG such that most operational programmes planned both the Olympic and Paralympic Games.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] The internal organisation of SOCOG evolved over the phases of the project and changed, sometimes radically, several times.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] In late 1998, the design was principally functional.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] The top two tiers below the CEO Sandy Hollway consisted of five groups (managed by Group General Managers and the Deputy CEO) and twenty divisions (managed by divisional General Managers), which in turn were further broken up into programmes and sub-programmes or projects.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] In 1999, functional areas (FAs) broke up into geographic precinct and venue teams (managed by Precinct Managers and Venue Managers) with functional area staff reporting to both the FA manager and the venue manager.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] The Interstate Football division extant in 1998 was the first of these geographically based venue teams.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] The origins of the volunteer program for Sydney 2000 dates back to the bid, as early as 1992.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] On 17 December 1992, a group of Sydney citizens interested in the prospect of hosting the 2000 Olympic and Paralympic Games gathered for a meeting at Sports House at Wentworth Park in Sydney.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] In the period leading up to 1999, after Sydney had won the bid, the small group of volunteers grew from approximately 42 to around 500.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] These volunteers became known as Pioneer Volunteers.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] The Pioneer Volunteer program was managed internally by SOCOG's Volunteer Services Department in consultation with prominent peak groups like The Centre for Volunteering (Volunteering and TAFE.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] Some of the Pioneer Volunteers still meet every four months, an unseen legacy of the Games which brought together a community spirit not seen before.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] During the Olympic games, tens of thousands of volunteers (the official figure placed at 46,967) helped everywhere at the Olympic venues and elsewhere in the city.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] They were honoured with a parade like the athletes had a few days before.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] The original festivals in Olympia celebrated both cultural events and physical feats.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] The tradition continued with the first modern Olympics in 1896, and since then various cultural events have accompanied the sporting competition.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] Starting with the 1996 Summer Olympics, a cycle of four arts festivals have been staged by each host country.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] The Sydney Olympic Arts Festival was an arts festival that ran before and during the Olympics.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] The festival event coordinator was David Gallen.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] The first of the four festivals was the first edition of the Festival of the Dreaming, which was founded by artistic director Rhoda Roberts (who later co-directed segments of the Opening Ceremony), was held in 1997, as the first of four leading up to the Sydney Olympics.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] Some events were held at the Sydney Opera House, and the festival included an Aboriginal cast performing Shakespeare's *A Midsummer Night's Dream*, as well as Samuel Beckett's *Waiting for Godot* performed in the Bundjalung language.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] The second festival was "A Sea Change", in which artists and companies from Australia and Oceania explored "the influence of the sea on Australian life as a means to explore the changing political and cultural climates in Australia".
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] The fourth and final festival, while featuring many international artists and companies, served as a showcase for the diversity and depth of the arts in Australia.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] Opening four weeks before the Olympic Games, the Sydney 2000 Olympics Arts Festival ran until the last day of athletic competition, from 18 August to 1 October 2000.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] Starting with an all-day Aboriginal welcoming ceremony, *Tubowgule* ("the Meeting of the Waters"), choreographed by Stephen Page, began at La Perouse beach near Botany Bay, and concluded at Bennelong Point, in the forecourt of Sydney Opera House.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] There, contemporary Indigenous dance company Bangarra Dance Theatre performed *Energy of Australia*.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] The gala opening event for the festival was the musically pyrotechnical "Symphony of a Thousand" by Mahler at the Sydney SuperDome.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] The festival included many performing arts events, mostly presented at the Sydney Opera House.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] There were also dance, singing, and drama performances, staged mainly at the Opera House but also at Her Majesty's Theatre and the Capitol Theatre.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] Only two plush toys of Fatso were made, one of which was placed in the Olympic Village; the plush was controversially smuggled into a medal ceremony by the Australian men's 4 × 200-metre relay team.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] The character achieved a cult following, with some Australians preferring Fatso to the actual mascots.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] One of the Fatso plushes was auctioned for charity following the Games (being sold to Kerry Stokes, an executive of the Seven Network, for A$80,450), while a figure of Fatso was included in an display outside Stadium Australia that commemorated the Games' volunteers.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] A total of 750 gold, 750 silver and 780 bronze medals were minted for the Games.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] The gold and silver medals contained 99.99 percent of pure silver.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] The bronze medals were 99 percent bronze with one percent silver, they were made by melting down Australian one-cent and two-cent coins, which had been removed from circulation from 1992 onward.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] The bouquets handed to medal recipients incorporated foliage from the Grevillea baileyana, also known as the white oak.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] The International Olympic Committee awarded Sydney and its inhabitants with the "Pierre de Coubertin Trophy" in recognition of the collaboration and happiness shown by the people of Sydney during the event to all the athletes and visitors around the world.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] After the Games had ended, the New South Wales Police Force was granted use of the Olympic Rings in a new commendation and citation as the IOC consideration after having staged the "safest" Games ever.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] The Australian Entertainment Mo Awards (commonly known informally as the Mo Awards), were annual Australian entertainment industry awards.
[src:seven-network/2000-summer-olympics] They recognise achievements in live entertainment in Australia from 1975 to 2016.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] The **Seven Network** (also known as **Channel Seven** or **Seven**) is one of Australia's major free-to-air television networks and media platforms.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] Based in Sydney, NSW, the **Seven Network** broadcasts a range of local Australian and foreign English-language programming across Australia, including factual television (e.g.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] **Seven News**), sports, reality television and scripted television programming.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] From the 1970s to 2025, **Seven** was operated by its Chairman and major stockholder, the conservative Australian media mogul and billionaire, Kerry Stokes, who retains a sizeable interest in **Seven** in 2026.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] Former **Seven West Media** director Teresa Dyson is the company's current chair.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] After *Seven's* merger with West Australian print publications in 2011, **Seven West Media** became a pillar of Stokes' once dominant, yet now declining, influence on Australian politics and society.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] Stokes' son Ryan Stokes is a board member, along with Stokes' former "right-hand man" Bruce McWilliam, who owns an additional 10% stake, thus cementing the Stokes family influence on the company for the foreseeable future.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] The platform also owns Australian publishing company Pacific Magazines and maintains a 33% stake in Sky News Australia.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] Seven's administration headquarters are in Eveleigh, Sydney, with the building having been completed in 2003.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] National news and current affairs programming are based at the flagship stations ATN-7 in Sydney and HSV-7 in Melbourne.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] In 2009, Seven moved its Sydney-based production operations from Epping to a purpose-built high-definition television production facility at the Australian Technology Park in Eveleigh.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] As of 2025, Seven is the highest-rated television network in Australia according to VOZ, ranking ahead of the Nine Network, ABC TV, Network 10, and SBS.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] Historically the network had struggled in the ratings since the 1960s, until the 2000s, not long after the introduction of the OzTAM ratings system in 2001.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] *Seven* responded to another drop in audience numbers in 2004, with a slate of newly commissioned local programming for 2005, the success of news and current affairs shows along with US-produced series in the late 2000s, leading to a significant and lasting boost in its audience.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] During the 2011 ratings season, Seven achieved the highest total viewer ratings across all 40 weeks of the rating year, the first network to accomplish this since OzTAM ratings began.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] In 2014, Seven Network had attained the second-largest viewership in Australia, and by 2020s had finally made it to the top of the ratings ladder.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] Early in the digital era, Seven provided a 576p enhanced-definition service through digital TV.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] On 18 March 2007, test simulcasts for 1080i commenced in the Sydney and Melbourne markets, Adelaide and Perth followed on 24 June 2007, with Brisbane following on 25 June 2007, and regional Queensland on 26 June 2007.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] The 1080i high definition version was then replaced by the new youth orientated 7mate channel in MPEG4 HD, and Seven was broadcast only in standard definition MPEG2.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] On 1 April 2008, ATN Sydney began broadcasting a digital signal to Foxtel and Austar's satellite and cable subscribers.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] On 5 February 2025, *Seven Network* began the discontinuation of standard definition signal, to became high-definition (HD) only across Australia, phasing out older MPEG-2technology in favour of MPEG-4.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] Adelaide transitioned first, on 5 February, followed by Perth on 30 April, and Brisbane on 9 July.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] The Sydney market was scheduled to transition 7 October 2025, with Melbourne being the final metropolitan region to switch on 27 February 2026.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] The transition affects Channels 7, 70, and 71, with 7two now HD only, whereas other digital channels such as 7mate and 7Bravo had already operated in MPEG4 HD.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] Viewers with older TVs have the need to perform a channel re-scan in 2026, or purchase a new TV or HD-compatible set-top box to continue receiving the *Seven* service.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] Seven's core programming is fibre-fed out of HSV Melbourne to sister stations and regional affiliates, with ATN Sydney providing national news and current affairs programming.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] Seven Network programming is also carried by third-party affiliate WIN Television in Mount Gambier, the Riverland of South Australia and the Murrumbidgee Irrigation Area of New South Wales.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] The 7HD multichannel was produced from October 2007 until 25 September 2010, discontinued, then later revived on 10 May 2016.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] The revival version initially broadcast split services: identical main channel programming for Melbourne and Adelaide, and continuous programming from 7mate for other metropolitan cities in 1080i MPEG-4 HD via Freeview.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] The split was implemented to allow broadcast of Australian rules football (AFL) matches in HD.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] By 16 December 2016, *Seven* quietly shifted to main channel programming on a long-term basis for Sydney, Brisbane and Perth.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] *PLUS7* was subsequently terminated 31 March 2018.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] On 23 July 2020, *7plus* introduced a new logo styled as **7+**.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] Seven Network's news service is called *Seven News* (formerly *Australian Television News (ATVN)* and *Seven National News*).
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] The Seven News division produces the *Seven News* flagship locally produced 6pm news broadcast, in addition to *Seven Afternoon News,* *Seven News: Spotlight Sunrise, The Morning Show,* and *Weekend Sunrise*.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] The following year, Seven's news and public affairs ratings began to increase in viewers, with *Today Tonight* challenging rival *A Current Affair*, and the new format of *Sunrise* leading to increased competition with Nine Network's *Today*.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] Seven's evening news bulletins also started to take the lead, with success in most cities.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] Seven has exclusive contracts with NBC News, ITN, and Three (New Zealand) to repackage international news coverage.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] During the early hours of 4am to 6am, Seven rebroadcasts portions of US television network NBC's news and current affairs programming, including *Today* and *Meet the Press*.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] In 1988, Seven adopted NBC News' main theme song, *The Mission*, for *Seven News*.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] On 5 July 2008, *Seven* introduced a watermark on news and current affairs programming.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] After trailing for many decades to *Nine News* (previously *National Nine News*) and *10 News* (previously *Ten Eyewitness News* and *10 News First*) in markets, *Seven News* rebounded from February 2005 onward, claiming Australia's number one television news and current affairs service.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] Under the guidance of former long-time *Nine News* chief Peter Meakin, Seven's news and current affairs division has produced more locally focused content, lifting viewership for key markets such as Sydney and Melbourne.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] Between 2007 and 2010, *Seven News* completed a clean sweep of the five capital cities, as the most watched 6pm news bulletin.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] Since February 2005, ratings for *Deal or No Deal*, *Seven News* and *Today Tonight* have gradually increased.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] *Seven News* was the highest-rated news service nationally in both the 2005 and 2006 ratings seasons.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] A key aspect of Seven's recent ratings dominance in news and current affairs has been attributed to *Deal or No Deal's* top rating audience (and, since late 2015, audiences for*The Chase Australia*), which provide *Seven News* with a big lead-in audience.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] From 2010, Seven Network began to create a five to 20-minute delay in the scheduled start time of non-live programming after 7:30pm, in an attempt to minimise viewer channel surfing and loss of audience to other networks.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] Commercial breaks are first increased in duration to create the delay, then decreased once prime time is over.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] Seven is a major purchaser of Australian sports broadcasting rights.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] The network had the exclusive coverage of the 2000 Sydney Olympics, which attracted a TV audience of over 6.5 million Australians for the opening and closing ceremonies.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] The broadcast also ran on the short-lived C7 Sport subscription channel.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] On 25 January 2001, Network Ten, Nine Network, and pay TV provider Foxtel won the rights from Seven to televise AFL games from 2002 to 2006.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] This ended Seven's famous 45-year run as the exclusive AFL football broadcaster.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] On 5 January 2006 the Australian Football League accepted a bid from Seven and Ten to broadcast AFL games from 2007 to 2011 at a cost of A$780 million.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] Since 2011, Seven has been the exclusive free-to-air broadcaster of the AFL Premiership Season to at least 2031.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] Seven had exclusive Australian free-to-air, pay television, online and mobile telephony broadcast rights to the 2008 Summer Olympics in Beijing.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] The live telecast of the XXIX Olympiad was shared by both Seven Network and SBS Television.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] Seven broadcast the opening and closing ceremonies and mainstream sports including swimming, athletics, rowing, cycling and gymnastics.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] In stark contrast, SBS TV provided complementary coverage focused on long-form events such as soccer, road cycling, volleyball, and table tennis.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] In 2010, Seven launched new AFL and NRL based entertainment shows to take on Nine's *The AFL Footy Show* and *The NRL Footy Show* and provide a bargaining chip in negotiations for AFL and NRL broadcast rights.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] AFL series *The Bounce*, hosted by Peter Helliar, was pulled from the air after just five episodes.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] NRL series,*The Matty Johns Show*, hosted by former *Footy Show* host Matthew Johns, lasted one season.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] From 2016, Seven became the home of the Summer Olympic Games, Winter Olympic Games and the Summer Paralympic Games.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] The Network secured the Australian broadcast rights to the Olympic Games.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] In October 2020, it was named as the Australian broadcast service for the 2022 Winter Olympics in Beijing.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] In 2016, Seven Network won the broadcasting rights deal to be the main broadcaster of the 2017 Rugby League World Cup in Australia, beating the other regular rugby league broadcasting channels of Fox League and the Nine Network to secure the deal.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] Seven Network also screened the 2018 Commonwealth Games on the Gold Coast in April 2018, and the 2022 Commonwealth Games from Birmingham in July 2022.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] In 2018, Seven Network, in conjunction with Foxtel, acquired free-to-air broadcasting rights to cricket in Australia.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] This ended Nine's famous 45-year run as the exclusive cricket broadcaster and Ten's five-year run as the exclusive Big Bash League broadcaster.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] The network will televise all men's international test matches, 43 Big Bash League Matches, all women's Internationals (T20Is, ODIs and Tests) and 23 Women's Big Bash League Matches.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] The six-year deal starts in 2018/19 and runs until 2023/24.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] In 2023, Seven announced that it reached an agreement with Cricket Australia to extend its media rights from the 2024–25 season to the 2030–31 season.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] The new seven-year agreement between Seven and Cricket Australia includes two Ashes Test Series as well as two Indian tours of Australia.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] In addition, Cricket Australia will revamp the BBL to create a shorter tournament that will run for five to six weeks to screen on the Seven network.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] From 2017 to 2024, the AFL Premiership Season and cricket matches were not accessible through the 7plus live streaming service given the digital broadcast rights were owned by Telstra Media and Kayo Sports respectively.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] *Border Security International* repeats played on the channel's live stream in the event's place until the match was over, before returning to normal programming.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] In 2020, Seven regained the TV rights to the Supercars Championship, sharing the rights with Foxtel in a deal worth $200 million for 5 years (2021–2025).
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] In 2024, Nine Network won the rights to broadcast the Olympic Games until 2032.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] Seven Network announced it will still broadcast Glasgow 2026 and 2030 Commonwealth Games live and free across Australia on TV, digital and 7plus Sport.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] Commensurate with Australian content rules for commercial broadcasters, *Seven* features local programming on the network.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] Similarly to other commercial broadcasters in Australia, programming is heavily focused on reality television and lifestyle content.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] However, shows range from original drama series e.g.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] *RFDS: Royal Flying Doctor Service* and *Packed to the Rafters;* soaps such as*Home and Away;* lifestyle magazine shows e.g.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] *Better Homes and Gardens;* game shows e.g.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] *The Chase Australia,* *The 1% Club*; entertainment e.g.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] The 1980s saw *Channel Seven* launch some of Australia's most iconic television drama and soaps.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] *A Country Practice* was first broadcast in 1981, running for twelve years, with and *Sons and Daughters* launched the following year in 1982.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] The Australian version of US game show *Wheel of Fortune* began its 25-year run in July 1981, from ADS-7's studios in Adelaide.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] Prime-time police drama *Blue Heelers* was commissioned in 1993, then bumped in 1998 from its prime-time slot, by medical drama *All Saints*.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] Game show *Australian Gladiators* had ratings success over three seasons, from 1995 to 1998.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] Lifestyle programming became a hot new format, with *Seven's* first iteration of travel show *The Great Outdoors* *(1993-2009), and Better Homes and Gardens,* winner of 12 Silver Logies for Most Popular Lifestyle Program, which debuted in 1995 and has run regularly ever since.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] Despite the success of new US-produced shows, Seven still finished second behind the Nine Network for the fifth time in six years, primarily due to Nine's coverage of the 2006 Commonwealth Games in Melbourne.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] In 2007 *Seven* defeated *Nine*, winning 38 weeks compared to the *Nine Network's* 2, to become the number one network in Australia.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] *Seven's* 2008 launch of local drama *Packed to the Rafters* became the year's top rated show with an average of 1.938 million viewers.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] In 2011, *Seven* put *Packed to the Rafters* on hiatus, putting new Melbourne drama *Winners and Losers* in its place, which soon became a network staple, at times winning the nation's highest ratings.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] In 2013, Seven Network launched a successful fifth local drama *A Place to Call Home*.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] In September 2015, the network launched *The Chase Australia,* a spinoff of the British series *The Chase*, featuring Chasers Anne Hegerty (from the British series), Brydon Coverdale (winner of $307,000 on *Million Dollar Minute*), Matt Parkinson and Issa Schultz.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] In 2016, Mark Labbett made his debut as one of the Chasers, joining fellow UK Chaser, Anne Hegerty and in 2018, Shaun Wallace made his debut as its sixth chaser.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] Seven also launched Australian comedy-drama *800 Words* starring Erik Thomson, becoming the highest-rated drama of 2015.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] In June 2020, *Big Brother Australia* made a return on Seven Network with a rebooted pre-recorded program.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] Hosted by Sonia Kruger, the series was prerecorded in a warehouse in Sydney, described by *TV Blackbox* as "Survivor in a warehouse".
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] The exact location is North Head Sanctuary, also known as The Barracks.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] Seven announced in 2020 the acquisition of reality series *The Voice Australia* in 2021 as well as a reboot of *Australian Idol*.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] Seven confirmed in December 2020 it had commissioned a return to a new "all stars" event version of *Dancing With The Stars*.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] The *Australian Idol* reboot returned to the screens of Seven in 2023.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] On *7two*, in the early 2010s, Seven aired classic and silver-screen movies from the Sony Pictures (Columbia & TriStar) catalogue.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] In mid-2013 the network changed its deals with Sony and NBCUniversal.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] Commensurate with the American network's own slump, Seven had not found success with an NBC prime time series since 2007.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] Seven renegotiated its NBCUniversal deal to continue rights to air existing popular NBC co-produced programs including *Downton Abbey* and *Mrs Brown's Boys*, as well as NBC News content.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] Seven signed a three-year minimum quota deal with Sony, whereby Seven will agree to purchase a set number of Sony produced US prime time series and films per year, with titles to be cherry-picked each season.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] In late 2016, Seven created a new acquired programming deal with Warner Bros, granting the network programming rights.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] In 2018 it was reported that Seven had formed an agreement with 20th Century Fox to air selected Fox programming.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] On 15 January 2023, Seven created a new acquired programming deal with NBCUniversal, granting the network programming rights.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] Shared American programming that airs on Seven and Nine and their digital multi-channels are sourced from Seven and Nine's deals with 20th Century Studios / 20th Television, Warner Bros.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] International Television Distribution, DreamWorks and DreamWorks Animation, NBCUniversal Global Distribution / Illumination, StudioCanal and Sony Pictures Television.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] Shared American programming that airs on Seven and 10 and their digital multi-channels are sourced from Seven and 10's deals with CBS Studios, DreamWorks / DreamWorks Animation, Warner Bros.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] International Television Distribution and Sony Pictures Television.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] Shared American programming that airs on Seven and ABC and their digital multi-channels are sourced from Seven and ABC's deals with NBCUniversal Global Distribution, StudioCanal and Sony Pictures Television.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] Due to Seven's coverage of the 2008 Summer Olympics, the International Olympic Committee awarded Seven the 'Golden Rings' award for "Best Olympic Programme".
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] The award is given for the best overall Olympic coverage.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] At the 2018 Sport Australia media awards, Seven won the "Best coverage of a sporting event" award for the coverage of the 2018 Commonwealth Games in Gold Coast.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] Seven Network's coverage of the Tokyo 2020 Summer Olympic Games saw them win three awards (gold, silver and bronze) at the International Olympic Committee's coveted Golden Rings Awards.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] The present Seven Network began in the 1950s as a group of independent stations in Sydney, Melbourne, Brisbane, Adelaide and Perth.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] HSV-7 Melbourne, licensed to *The Herald and Weekly Times* Ltd (owners of two local papers at the time, *The Herald* and *The Sun*), was launched on 4 November 1956, as Melbourne's first television station to use the VHF7 frequency.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] ATN-7 Sydney, licensed to Amalgamated Television Services, a subsidiary of Fairfax, was launched on 2 December 1956, as Sydney's third television station.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] HSV-7 and ATN-7 did not immediately share resources, but instead formed content-sharing partnerships with their VHF9 counterparts.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] By 1957 ATN-7 partnered with Melbourne's GTV-9, while HSV-7 paired up with Sydney's TCN-9.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] TVW-7 Perth, licensed to TVW Limited, a subsidiary of West Australian Newspapers, began broadcasting almost two years later, on 16 October 1959, becoming Perth's first television station.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] BTQ-7 Brisbane followed on 1 November 1959, as Brisbane's second television station.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] ADS-7 Adelaide was launched on 24 October 1959 as the final capital city VHF7 station.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] The station later swapped frequencies with SAS-10 on 27 December 1987 as ADS-10 and SAS-7.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] HSV-7 began its relationship with the Victorian Football League (now the Australian Football League) in April 1957, when the station broadcast the first live Australian rules football match.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] At the time, the stations operated independently of each other, with schedules made up of various simple programs that were inexpensive to produce, such as *Pick a Box* and spin-offs of popular radio shows.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] In the early 1960s, coaxial cable links were formed initially between Sydney and Melbourne, which allowed the sharing of programs and simultaneous broadcasts of live TV shows.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] In 1960, Frank Packer, the owner of Sydney's TCN-9, bought a controlling share of Melbourne's GTV-9.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] This created the country's first television network (unofficially called "the National Nine Network") and dissolved the ATN-7/GTV-9 and the HSV-7/TCN-9 partnerships.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] Left without their original partners, ATN-7 and HSV-7 joined to form the Australian Television Network (ATN) in 1963.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] The new grouping was soon joined by other capital-city channel 7 stations, ADS-7 Adelaide and BTQ-7 Brisbane.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] ATN began to produce and screen higher-budget programs to attract viewers, notably the Australian show *Homicide* (1964–1977), a series that would continue for another 12 years to become the nation's longest running drama series of the period.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] After the network adopted the *Network 7* name in 1970, a national network logo was adopted.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] Stations remained independently owned and operated with local adveristing campaigns.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] Color television was introduced across the network in 1975, when a new colour logo was adopted.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] In 1979, Rupert Murdoch made an unsuccessful bid for the *Herald and Weekly Times*, owners of HSV-7, later going on to gain control of rival ATV-10.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] Fairfax successfully bought a 14.9% share of Network 7 later that same year.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] A decade of media magnates jostling for control of Australian's media landscape was to follow.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] The 1980s saw the introduction of stereophonic sound, as well as several successful shows, most notably *A Country Practice* in 1981, and *Sons and Daughters* in 1982.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] The 1980 Summer Olympics in Moscow were shown live on the network in 1980.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] *Neighbours* began on Seven in 1985, but low ratings in Sydney led to the cancellation of the new series at the end of the year, which later moved to Network 10 and went on to achieve international success.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] Perth-based businessman Robert Holmes à Court, through his business the Bell Group, bought TVW-7 from its original owners, West Australian Newspapers in 1982.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] It was in 1984 that the network proceeded to drop the "Network 7" branding.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] *The Herald and Weekly Times*, owner of HSV-7 and ADS-7, was sold to Rupert Murdoch in December 1986 for an estimated $1.8 billion.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] Murdoch's company, News Limited, sold off HSV-7 to Fairfax soon afterwards for $320 million.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] Fairfax went on to remove a number of locally produced shows in favour of networked content from its Sydney counterpart, ATN-7 (also owned by Fairfax at the time).
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] Cross-media ownership laws introduced in 1987 forced Fairfax to choose between its print and television operations.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] Fairfax chose print and sold its television stations to Qintex Ltd., owned by businessman Christopher Skase.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] Qintex had previously bought, and subsequently sold off, stations in Brisbane and regional Queensland before taking control of the network.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] It was also in 1987 that the network returned to the "Australian Television Network" branding.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] The next year, another new logo was introduced along with the evening soap *Home and Away* and a relaunched *Seven National News*, now known as *Seven News*.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] The network became truly national in 1988 when Skase bought TVW-7 for $130 million.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] In 1991, the network changed its name once again to Seven Network, though it had been unofficially using that name for some time before then.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] Despite the network's successes, a failed $1.5 billion bid for MGM Studios in the same year sent Qintex into receivership.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] Christopher Skase fled Australia in 1990 to escape extradition.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] The business' assets were bundled together by receivers and made into a new company, Seven Network Limited, in 1991.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] The network was listed on the stock exchange in 1993, soon after the entry of subscription television provider Australis.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] One of Seven's popular series, *A Country Practice*, ended in 1993 after 1058 episodes.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] *Blue Heelers* was also introduced in 1993, and, after a number of time-slot changes, was moved to Wednesdays in 1998.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] This was to make room for a new series, the medical drama *All Saints*.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] Both dramas rated quite highly and along with new lifestyle shows *Better Homes and Gardens* and *The Great Outdoors*, resulted in a stronger ratings position for the network.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] In 1995, Sunshine Television, a Seven Network affiliate in regional Queensland, was purchased by the network's parent company, Seven Network Limited.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] Sunshine Television's regional stations effectively became a part of Seven Network, identical in appearance and programming to the rest of the business' stations.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] Australian Gladiators proved popular; Series 1 and 2 were filmed in Brisbane in 1995–1996, and Series 3 was filmed in Sydney.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] Seven Queensland won the annual audience ratings for the first time in 1998.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] Between 1995 and April 2001, Alan Jackson of Nylex was the non-executive director of Seven, after being asked by Stokes to lead the company.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] A successful $1.3 billion bid for United Artists was made in conjunction with Kirk Kerkorian in 1996, but the network sold its stake two years later for US$389 million.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] Seven took control of *Australia Television,* the Australian Broadcasting Corporation's Asian satellite channel, in 1997.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] The Australian Broadcasting Corporation still maintained a share in the network and continued to produce news and current affairs programming for it.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] During the late 1990s and early 2000s, a high-definition national broadcast facility was constructed in Docklands, Melbourne, replacing the previous facility in Epping, Sydney.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] This new facility would also house HSV-7's Melbourne offices and studios.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] The year 2000 saw former Nine executive David Leckie appointed as head of television operations, re-launching the network with an updated logo and a new advertising campaign timed for the network's coverage of the 2000 Summer Olympics in Sydney.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] The opening ceremony, with 6.5 million viewers, was one of Australia's highest-ever rating television programs, contributing to the network winning the ratings year for the first time in twenty-two years.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] Digital television was introduced to most of the network's coverage area on 1 January 2001.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] This was soon followed by the gradual introduction of wide screen and high definition programming.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] In January 2006, Seven Network, Pacific Magazines and online portal Yahoo!
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] Australia and New Zealand combined in a joint venture to form Yahoo!7, representing all three companies' online assets.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] On 15 September 2007, 7HD was officially announced with the Seven Media Group announcing their intention to start a high definition multichannel that was initially expected to launch in December 2007.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] 7HD became the first free-to-air commercial television channel introduced to metropolitan areas since 1988, when it launched prior on 15 October 2007, with *25th Hour* being the first program broadcast at 10:30 pm.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] On 14 February 2008, the Seven Media Group and Foxtel officially signed an agreement allowing Seven's digital signal to be transmitted via Foxtel's cable and satellite services.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] Seven became available on Foxtel in early 2009.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] On 25 September 2009, Seven announced its new digital channel, 7two, which officially launched on 1 November 2009.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] On 18 January 2010, Seven launched the online catch-up TV website called *PLUS7*.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] On 25 September 2010, in conjunction with the 2010 AFL Grand Final, Seven launched its second multi-digital channel 7mate.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] 7mate is targeted towards a male audience, particularly those aged between 16 and 49.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] In January 2011, the big red 7 logos were expanded to GWN7 and Prime7's rebranding respectively.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] The news bulletins were renamed as *GWN7 News* and *Prime7 News*.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] GWN and Prime relaunched on 16 January 2011 at 6:00 pm, and its digital channels were branded as 7two and 7mate.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] In December 2011, Seven announced its intention to expand into digital datacasting known as 4ME, a digital channel owned by the Prime Media Group on channel 64 in Prime7 and regional areas and Channel 74 in other areas.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] In October 2012, Seven began cost-cutting by shedding a number of behind-the-scenes technical positions.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] Seven also reduced their SNG transponder link capacity on Optus D1 from three (at 12.661,12.671 & 12.681 GHz) to two (at 12.644 & 12.653 GHz), which are used by ATN Sydney for Sunrise and national news location up-links, as well as for other local station location up-links.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] In November 2012, Seven changed its on-air theme.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] This included a new look for program advisory ratings, program listings, program advertisements, and promotions.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] As of 10 December 2013, Seven no longer broadcasts on analogue TV and is now only available through digital TV or digital set-top box.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] On 26 June 2015, Racing.com began broadcasting on channel 78 as a joint venture between Seven West Media and Racing Victoria following a blackout of Victorian horse racing by Sky Racing.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] Initially broadcasting an interim live feed from the Racing.com website, the channel was officially launched on 29 August 2015.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] In January 2016, Seven changed its on-air theme.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] This included a new look for program listings, program advertisements and promotions.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] On 7 February 2016, during the ad-break of *Molly*, after months of speculation, Seven officially announced their new channel, 7flix, on channel 76.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] 7flix was launched at 6 am on 28 February 2016.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] On 10 May 2016, 7HD returned as a high definition simulcast on channel 70.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] Initially, the Melbourne and Adelaide markets received 7HD as a HD simulcast of Seven's primary channel, while the Sydney, Brisbane and Perth markets received 7HD as an HD simulcast of 7mate; this was to allow Australian Football League (AFL) matches to be broadcast in HD in those markets.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] Sydney, Brisbane and Perth temporarily received 7HD as a simulcast of the primary channel for the duration of the 2016 Summer Olympics before the change was made permanent during and after the 2017 Australian Open.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] Up until 16 January 2020, breakaway programming was used to show further AFL matches and Australian cricket matches in HD.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] In June 2017, following the acquisition of Yahoo! by Verizon Communications, Seven announced plans to launch a wholly owned standalone service to replace PLUS7.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] In September 2017, Seven announced the new service would be known as *7plus* and would launch in November 2017.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] As of September 2017, Seven's live streaming service, now named 7Live, is no longer accessible from within the PLUS7 and the Yahoo7 portal.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] On 1 December 2018, Seven announced **7food Network**, a new digital channel, which launched on channel 74.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] The announcement with Discovery Network followed SBS Food network losing its deal with Discovery-owned Scripps Network.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] The channel ceased broadcast on 28 December 2019, just over a year after it launched, though Seven continued to utilise the Food Network branding elsewhere.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] In June 2020, *Big Brother Australia* made a return on the Seven Network with a reboot.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] On the night of the premiere, *Seven* also changed their on-air theme.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] On 19 June 2020, it was announced that *The Daily Edition* had been cancelled by Seven Network after 7 years, and hosts Sally Obermeder and Ryan Phelan would be leaving the network.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] The final episode aired on 26 June 2020.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] In July 2020, Seven Network unveiled new logos for its multi-channels, beginning with 7mate, followed by 7two and 7flix.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] The re-branding also extended to its on-demand platform, 7plus, which was stylised as "7+" as part of a broader branding overhaul of its multichannel services.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] In March 2021, it was announced that Seven Network would move out of Martin Place to Eveleigh in 2022, after almost two decades.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] On 1 November 2021, Seven West Media announced that it would acquire all the shares and subsidiaries of Prime Media Group.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] This development would mark an end to the Prime branding after 33 years in favour of Seven Network's branding and would see all news bulletins carry the Seven News brand.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] It was also announced that Seven would look to expand its investment in local news following the merger.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] A majority of Prime's shareholders voted in favour of the deal on 23 December, with the sale completed on 31 December.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] Commencing June 2022, Seven moved to a national brand across all of its regions, in time for the 2022 Commonwealth Games.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] Introduced to regional audiences on 6 June 2022, viewers in those markets began to see the Prime7 and GWN7 logos transition into the national Seven branding.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] Seven announced in October 2022 it would launch a new free-to-air channel, 7Bravo on 15 January 2023, on LCN 75 in metropolitan areas and LCN 65 in regional areas.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] As a result, ishop TV moved from LCN 65 to LCN 67 in the former Prime7 areas.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] 7Bravo shows reality shows and true crime.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] The launch is a partnership between Seven Network and NBCUniversal International Networks & Direct-to-Consumer.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] On 30 November 2022, various channel changes on Seven Network happened to accommodate for the new 7Bravo channel, including a 7mate SD (Channel 73) switch-off.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] On the same day, 7Bravo on channel 75 appeared on the Seven multiplex, and ishop TV moving to channel 67 placeholder in seven regional areas.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] In June 2023, 7NEWS moved their operations from Martin Place to new purpose-built studios in Eveleigh, offering five times the space and permanent sets for all programs.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] For the first time in more than 40 years, the whole Seven Sydney operation, including all staff, were under one roof.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] In July 2023, *Sunrise* hosted its first broadcast at its new studios.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] The first edition went to air live at 5:30am on 24 July 2023, with hosts Natalie Barr and Matt Shirvington, news presenter Edwina Bartholomew and sports presenter Mark Beretta, followed by *The Morning Show'*s Larry Emdur and Kylie Gillies.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] On 22 January 2024, TVSN and Seven West Media signed a new broadcast deal, which means the channel will be on Seven from 1 July 2024, shifting from 10 and WIN Television.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] TVSN will be on channel 77 in metropolitan areas and regional Queensland, channel 67 in other regional areas and on 7plus nationally.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] In May 2025, Seven West Media announced its intention to purchase Southern Cross Austereo's regional Seven Network affiliate stations in Tasmania, Darwin, Spencer Gulf, Broken Hill, Mount Isa and Remote Central and Eastern Australia for $3.75 Million.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] Following a failure in negotiating a new affiliate deal with WIN Television, the Seven Network temporarily ceased broadcasting in Riverland, Griffith, and Mount Gambier from 1 July to 3 July 2025.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] Following Seven's acquisition of Southern Cross Austereo's television assets, Seven and Southern Cross Media Group (owners of SCA) announced in September 2025 their intention to merge.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] The merger was completed on 7 January 2026 with Seven West Media delisted from the ASX.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] In September 2011, Seven broadcast a report featuring journalist Tim Noonan and writer and adventurer Paul Raffaele visiting Brazil's Suruwahá tribe and describing them as child murderers, "Stone Age" relics, and "one of the worst human rights violators in the world".
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] Survival International, the global movement for tribal people's rights, sent a complaint to Seven outlining the many errors and distortions in the report.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] After the channel refused to correct the inaccuracies in the program, Survival filed a complaint with the Australian Communications and Media Authority (ACMA), which opened a formal investigation.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] In September 2012, the network was found guilty by the press regulator of serious violations of the broadcasting code.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] The ACMA ruled that the channel was guilty of breaking its racism clause – having "provoked or perpetuated intense dislike, serious contempt or severe ridicule against the Suruwahá people on the grounds of ... national or ethnic origin ... race [or] religion".
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] It also ruled that the channel was guilty of broadcasting inaccurate material.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] Seven sought judicial review, but in June 2014 the Federal Court upheld the ruling.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] In July–August 2023 when the 2023 FIFA Women's World Cup was hosted by Australia and New Zealand, there was some controversy worldwide about broadcasting rights to it, when broadcasters' offers were very low.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] FIFA's handling of the rights was also criticised.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] Seven Network won the rights to broadcast 15 of the matches.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] These included four round of 16 games, two quarter-finals, the semi-finals, and the final, along with all of the Matildas games.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] The pay channel Optus Sport has rights for every game in the tournament.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] This raised public criticism, with many arguing that the entire tournament should be free-to-air, as was the 2022 (men's) World Cup in Qatar, on SBS Television.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] In September 2023, a female Queensland contestant in an upcoming Seven Network reality show was charged with multiple counts of indecent treatment of children aged under 16, multiple counts of rape, sexual assault, torture and assaults over a 15-year period.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] Her partner was also charged with a number of assaults.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] Seven refused to confirm whether it will cancel or alter the program.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] On 14 April 2024, the network was under fire for misidentification of a Jewish student named Ben Cohen as the perpetrator of 2024 Bondi Junction stabbings.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] Some titles were exclusively available in Australia on PLUS7, including *Other Space* and *Sin City Saints*, as well as the British version of *My Kitchen Rules*, which were not broadcast on Seven Network.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p01] In 2014, PLUS7 became the first commercial television catch-up service to provide optional closed captioning on most of its programming.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p02] The network's first logo produced and used across the metropolitan stations in the early 1970s featured the numeral seven inside a ring (similar to the Circle 7 logo used mostly by the American Broadcasting Company for its owned-and-operated stations which ATN-7 used from 1968 to 1969).
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p02] In some states from as early back as 1967 the "Seven eye" appeared and continued until 1975.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p02] Colour television was introduced across the network and the country on 1 March 1975, along with a new logo incorporating a bright ring of the colours of the visual light spectrum.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p02] This logo was used nationally until 23 January 1989, when the Seven Network introduced a new red logo with the circle modified to incorporate the "7" (similar to the logo then used by WJLA-TV in Washington).
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p02] The new logo was rolled out along with evening soap *Home and Away* and a relaunched *Seven Nightly News* (later to become *Seven News*).
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p02] The current ribbon logo designed by Cato Brand Partners was launched looking forward to the new millennium celebration on 1 January 2000 and the 2000 Summer Olympics held in Sydney.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p02] The ribbon logo was used between 2000 and 2003 in five color variants: red, orange, yellow, green and blue, to symbolise *passion*, *involving*, *fun*, *life* and *energy* respectively and represents the five stations of the network.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p02] The logo was simplified in 2003, effectively becoming simply two angled trapezoids, losing its gradient, shadows and colour-coded usages to become solid red but first it was used in solid white as an on-screen bug from 2000.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p02] In 2012, the Seven logo was slightly modified with the shape of it remaining the same, the upper right corner was lighter red than the remaining logo.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p02] On 1 February 2016, it reverted to red trapezoids.
[src:seven-network/seven-network-p02] Seven Network's TV ad campaigns have often followed NBC due to Seven's historical ties with the American network, but has occasionally used branding from fellow US networks ABC and FOX.
